WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.134 --> 00:00:02.584
(gentle music)

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:06.070
- [Narrator] For millennia, the Grand Pyramids of Egypt

00:00:06.070 --> 00:00:08.722
have towered over the desert sands.

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:14.140
Everything about the great ancient civilization

00:00:14.140 --> 00:00:17.383
that once seized the lands remained a mystery.

00:00:19.060 --> 00:00:23.394
That is until July 19th, 1799.

00:00:23.394 --> 00:00:26.144
(dramatic music)

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:30.340
A French soldier discovers a large stone

00:00:30.340 --> 00:00:33.160
about 35 miles east of Alexandria

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:36.403
during Napoleon Bonaparte's Egyptian expedition,

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:40.900
unearthing a written language

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:44.440
that had been dead for thousands of years.

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:47.350
The translations would prove to be the key

00:00:47.350 --> 00:00:51.617
to unlocking the secrets of an entire civilization.

00:00:51.617 --> 00:00:54.367
(dramatic music)

00:01:01.427 --> 00:01:03.850
"Egypt is the gift of the Nile,"

00:01:03.850 --> 00:01:07.240
that's what Herodotus, the Father of History said.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:09.340
Since the Nile is the lifeline,

00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:11.320
as it provided Egypt with water

00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:13.210
for the cultivation of crops,

00:01:13.210 --> 00:01:15.910
which led to the burgeoning of civilization

00:01:15.910 --> 00:01:18.520
all along the length of the Nile Valley.

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:21.520
The river strip that divided the Egyptian territory

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:24.490
into two parts provided a favorable environment

00:01:24.490 --> 00:01:26.410
for the rise of civilization,

00:01:26.410 --> 00:01:29.890
when the Nile Valley began in the Miocene times,

00:01:29.890 --> 00:01:31.990
cutting it into its current shape.

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:34.570
The various geographical resources

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:37.690
effectively contributed to the state's foundation.

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:39.940
As a result of the annual floods

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:43.120
that spread the fertile soil to the east and west

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:46.420
over the centuries, mud deposits built up.

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:49.570
When the water recedes and flows along its banks,

00:01:49.570 --> 00:01:52.000
the agricultural year begins,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.080
making Egypt one of the first agricultural communities

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:59.470
that ever existed in human history.

00:01:59.470 --> 00:02:01.690
At the end of the Paleolithic era,

00:02:01.690 --> 00:02:04.330
there was a widespread production of arrows,

00:02:04.330 --> 00:02:07.420
harpoons, querns, sewed skins,

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:09.580
bone works, and pottery.

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:11.980
Carbon-14 tests, on the other hand,

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:14.320
were used by researchers to demonstrate

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:17.800
that corn was harvested in a Neolithic silo

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:21.440
on the edge of Thiam between 4600 and 4250 BC.

00:02:23.380 --> 00:02:25.600
Later, people built shacks and huts

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:27.520
out of reeds and solid mud,

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.090
and sowed corn on the muddy soil of the Nile marshes.

00:02:31.090 --> 00:02:34.360
Ancient Egypt was divided into two territories,

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:36.910
Upper Egypt and Lower Egypt.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:38.980
Lower Egypt laid to the north,

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:41.680
where the Nile extended out with its several branches

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:43.480
to form the Nile Delta.

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:46.090
Upper Egypt, which stretched to Aswan,

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:47.440
was to the south.

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:52.120
The two kingdoms were united around 3000 BC by King Narmer,

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:54.220
but each retained its regalia,

00:02:54.220 --> 00:02:57.430
the Hedjet or white crown for Upper Egypt,

00:02:57.430 --> 00:03:00.880
and the Deshret or red crown for Lower Egypt.

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:02.980
As a result, the pharaohs were known

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:05.560
as the rulers of the two lands,

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:06.970
and they wore the pschent,

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:08.950
a double crown with each half denoting

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:10.603
sovereignty of a different land.

00:03:14.474 --> 00:03:17.974
(vocalist gently singing)

00:03:33.589 --> 00:03:36.220
The Predynastic Period in ancient Egypt

00:03:36.220 --> 00:03:39.130
is the period preceding documented history,

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:43.720
encompassing around 6,000 to 3150 BCE,

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:46.930
from the Paleolithic to the Neolithic age,

00:03:46.930 --> 00:03:49.840
and onto the founding of the First Dynasty.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:52.810
While there are no written records from this period,

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:55.960
archeological digs in Egypt have unearthed items

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:57.310
that convey their tale

00:03:57.310 --> 00:04:00.370
of the Nile River Valley's cultural history.

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:03.130
The Predynastic Period is called by the regions

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:04.930
or ancient city sites

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:06.880
where these artifacts were discovered,

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:09.667
rather than the cultures that lived there.

00:04:09.667 --> 00:04:14.080
The Halfan culture thrived circa 30,000 BCE

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:17.050
in the area between Egypt and Nubia,

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:19.900
giving birth to the Qadan and Sebilian cultures

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:24.310
around 10,000 BCE, and the Harifan culture.

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:27.520
All of these cultures are hunter-gatherer societies

00:04:27.520 --> 00:04:30.220
that gradually grew more sedentary,

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:32.680
and settled into more permanent settlements

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:34.270
based on agriculture.

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:37.000
The Faiyum Oasis is a natural basin

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.760
located southeast of the Giza Plateau

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:42.640
that gave home to the Faiyum A civilization

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:46.120
during 9,000 to 6,000 BCE.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:49.120
These people lived in the vicinity of a vast lake,

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:51.310
and made their living through agriculture,

00:04:51.310 --> 00:04:52.750
hunting and fishing.

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.450
The people of Faiyum constructed reed homes

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:58.660
with subterranean basements for food storage.

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:01.360
Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated,

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:04.660
and basketry and pottery production flourished.

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:06.970
During this period, tribal chieftains

00:05:06.970 --> 00:05:10.390
assumed positions of power, which may have been passed down

00:05:10.390 --> 00:05:13.570
to the next generation in a family or tribal unit.

00:05:13.570 --> 00:05:16.960
Communities went from tiny tribes traveling together

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:20.050
to large groupings of diverse tribes

00:05:20.050 --> 00:05:23.050
living in the same region all the time.

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:26.110
The Faiyum A culture gave rise to the Merimde

00:05:26.110 --> 00:05:29.500
during 5,000 to 4,000 BCE,

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:31.690
which was named from artifacts discovered

00:05:31.690 --> 00:05:33.580
at the location of that name

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:36.040
on the western side of the Nile Delta.

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:38.530
The majority of Egyptians were farmers,

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:40.600
and agriculture was the basis

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:42.940
of the Dynastic Egypt economy,

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:45.790
and farmers relied on the annual summer floods

00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:47.260
to grow their crops.

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:49.480
We know that the first Egyptian farmers

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:51.010
were hunter-gatherers.

00:05:51.010 --> 00:05:52.810
They planted crops such as wheat,

00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:55.540
lentils, barley, flax, and peas,

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:57.433
in addition to herding animals.

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:00.520
According to what was found in a location

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:02.980
in the western side of the Nile Delta,

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:05.560
the oldest levels of Merimde Beni Salama

00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:09.670
that evolved between 8,000 and 4,000 BC,

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:11.770
in addition to the Faiyum Basin,

00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:14.200
both dating back to the Neolithic era.

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:16.420
The Nile Valley's convex terrain

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:19.420
encouraged the development of several basins,

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:21.610
which in ancient times were flooded

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:24.520
with flood waters every year that brought silt

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:26.800
and mud that fertilized the soil.

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:30.280
These basins, of which 130 have been found,

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:32.440
served as the irrigation systems,

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:34.963
reservoirs in ancient Egypt.

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:39.520
Granaries were made of clay jars or baskets

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.980
that were buried up to their necks in the earth.

00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:45.910
The El Omari culture, about 4,000 BCE,

00:06:45.910 --> 00:06:47.440
developed on these achievements

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:49.300
by building circular homes,

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:52.900
of higher complexity with plastered mud walls.

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:54.550
All of these cultures evolved

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:56.710
and flourished in Lower Egypt,

00:06:56.710 --> 00:06:59.680
Northern Egypt, closest to the Mediterranean sea,

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:03.373
whereas Upper Egypt civilization formed later.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:06.790
The inhabitants of the Badarian culture

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:08.410
lived in movable tents,

00:07:08.410 --> 00:07:12.370
like their ancient forefathers, but preferred fixed homes.

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:14.170
Following the Badarian period

00:07:14.170 --> 00:07:18.310
came the Amratian period, also known as Naqada I,

00:07:18.310 --> 00:07:20.500
which constructed more complex homes

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:23.950
with windows and hearths, wattle and daub walls,

00:07:23.950 --> 00:07:26.440
and windbreaks around the main entryway.

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:31.440
The practice of mummification began around 3,500 BCE,

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:34.840
where burial items were still left with the deceased.

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:37.930
These developments were aided by the Gerzean culture,

00:07:37.930 --> 00:07:42.930
also known as Naqada II, 3,500 to 3,200 BCE,

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:45.940
which launched trading with other regions,

00:07:45.940 --> 00:07:48.760
inspiring changes in culture and art.

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:51.280
The houses were built of sun baked brick,

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:54.280
and the more opulent ones included courtyards,

00:07:54.280 --> 00:07:56.350
an addition that would become commonplace

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:58.027
in Egyptian homes later.

00:07:58.027 --> 00:08:01.030
The city of Abydos, located north of Naqada,

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:03.850
became an important burial location,

00:08:03.850 --> 00:08:07.540
and huge tombs were built forming a necropolis,

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:09.010
a city of the dead.

00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:11.890
These tombs were originally made of mud bricks,

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:15.880
but subsequently of huge, neatly hewn limestone.

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:18.790
Eventually, this site would become the burial place

00:08:18.790 --> 00:08:20.710
for Egypt's rulers.

00:08:20.710 --> 00:08:22.720
Despite this, evidence reveals

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:25.420
that individuals from all across the nation

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:27.880
had their deceased buried at Abydos,

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:30.850
and gave burial gifts to commemorate their memory.

00:08:30.850 --> 00:08:33.850
By this time, the cities of Xois and Hierakonpolis

00:08:33.850 --> 00:08:35.350
were considered ancient,

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:38.803
while Thinis, Naqada and Nekhen were rapidly.

00:08:39.699 --> 00:08:41.110
Developing the hieroglyphic alphabet,

00:08:41.110 --> 00:08:45.370
which was invented around 3,400 to 3,200 BCE,

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:47.740
was used for maintaining records.

00:08:47.740 --> 00:08:49.930
Although no entire sentences

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:52.150
from this period have been discovered.

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:54.700
At this time, the earliest Egyptian writing

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:57.790
discovered so far originates from Abydos,

00:08:57.790 --> 00:08:59.590
and was discovered on pottery,

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:03.460
clay seal imprints, and bone and ivory items.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:06.070
Complete sentences are not found in Egypt

00:09:06.070 --> 00:09:08.080
until the time of King Peribsen

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:11.410
in the Second Dynasty 500 years later.

00:09:11.410 --> 00:09:14.260
This period led to the Naqada III period,

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:18.100
from 3,200 to 3,150 BCE.

00:09:18.100 --> 00:09:21.910
Following Naqada III, the Early Dynastic Period

00:09:21.910 --> 00:09:24.970
and Egypt's recorded history began.

00:09:24.970 --> 00:09:28.450
With commerce, communities expanded and flourished,

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:32.740
and the populations of both Lower and Upper Egypt increased.

00:09:32.740 --> 00:09:35.890
Small villages of brick dwellings and buildings evolved

00:09:35.890 --> 00:09:39.400
into bigger urban centers that soon clashed,

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:42.940
most likely for trade products and water resources.

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:44.683
Thinis, Naqada and Nekhen

00:09:44.683 --> 00:09:47.200
were the three principle city states

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:49.720
of Upper Egypt during the period.

00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:51.760
Thinis appears to have defeated Naqada

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:53.563
before absorbing Nekhen.

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:55.720
These battles were fought

00:09:55.720 --> 00:09:59.830
between the Scorpion Kings, whose identity is unknown.

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:02.740
And others, most likely Ka and Narmer.

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:04.690
According to some researchers,

00:10:04.690 --> 00:10:06.920
Scorpion I, Scorpion II and Ka

00:10:08.350 --> 00:10:10.390
were the final three rulers

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.640
of the Protodynastic Period,

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:17.290
before King Narmer invaded and unified Lower and Upper Egypt

00:10:17.290 --> 00:10:19.977
and created the First Dynasty.

00:10:19.977 --> 00:10:22.727
(dramatic music)

00:10:24.997 --> 00:10:28.330
(dramatic upbeat music)

00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:47.320
The Early Dynastic Period in Egypt

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:52.183
began in the years 3150 to 2613 BCE.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:54.460
This marks the beginning

00:10:54.460 --> 00:10:56.800
of the country's historical era,

00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:59.140
in which Upper Egypt, the south,

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:02.050
and Lower Egypt to the north were unified

00:11:02.050 --> 00:11:05.080
as one country under centralized authority.

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:08.620
During this time, the divine rule of the monarch started

00:11:08.620 --> 00:11:11.770
and a distinct Egyptian culture emerged,

00:11:11.770 --> 00:11:13.840
including the development of writing,

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:15.940
arts and sciences.

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:18.820
Menes, the first king of Egypt,

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:21.220
was a ruler of Upper Egypt,

00:11:21.220 --> 00:11:24.280
presumably from Thinis or Hierakonpolis,

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:27.010
who defeated the other city states around him

00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:31.900
before conquering Lower Egypt around 3,150 BCE.

00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:34.200
Narmer married the Princess Neithhotep

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:35.920
of Naqada in an arrangement

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:38.950
to enhance the links between the two towns.

00:11:38.950 --> 00:11:41.200
He undertook military operations

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:43.420
in Lower Egypt to quell revolts,

00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:46.540
and expand his territory into Cannan and Nubia.

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:49.660
He sponsored massive construction projects,

00:11:49.660 --> 00:11:52.870
and urbanization developed throughout his reign.

00:11:52.870 --> 00:11:55.510
Hor-Aha, Narmer's son, is assumed

00:11:55.510 --> 00:11:59.020
to have succeeded him in 3,100 BCE,

00:11:59.020 --> 00:12:01.960
continuing his father's military expansion

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:03.790
and increasing trade.

00:12:03.790 --> 00:12:06.280
He was notably interested in religion

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:08.350
and the concept of the afterlife,

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:12.070
and it was under his reign that the mastaba tomb was built.

00:12:12.070 --> 00:12:17.070
Hor-Aha was replaced by his son Djer in 3,050 BCE,

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:19.720
who followed in his father's footsteps.

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:23.410
His son Djet, about 3000 BCE,

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:25.150
married Princess Merneith,

00:12:25.150 --> 00:12:27.340
and is considered to have taken leadership

00:12:27.340 --> 00:12:29.473
of the nation after his death.

00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:34.690
It is uncertain whether she governed as regent

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:37.780
for her infant son Den or as queen,

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:41.230
but her reign is notable for being the first time

00:12:41.230 --> 00:12:44.680
a woman is recorded governing in ancient Egypt.

00:12:44.680 --> 00:12:48.730
Den, about 2,990 BCE, is regarded

00:12:48.730 --> 00:12:52.210
as the greatest monarch of the first dynasty

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:55.060
and reigned for 50 years.

00:12:55.060 --> 00:12:57.460
His reputation as an efficient monarch

00:12:57.460 --> 00:13:01.900
stemmed from his economic advances, military conquests,

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:04.120
and the stability of his rule,

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:07.270
as proven by expensive construction projects

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:09.310
and elaborate works of art.

00:13:09.310 --> 00:13:11.170
Den is the first monarch

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:13.060
to be represented wearing the crowns

00:13:13.060 --> 00:13:15.280
of Upper and Lower Egypt,

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:18.940
showing that he ruled over a unified nation.

00:13:18.940 --> 00:13:22.210
Den was succeeded by two additional monarchs,

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:24.430
Anedjib and later Semerkhet,

00:13:24.430 --> 00:13:28.180
both of whom had tough reigns marked by insurgency.

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:31.030
The dynasty ended with the Qa'a's reign,

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:33.820
during which his heirs struggled for the throne

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:36.940
and were defeated by Hotepsekhemwy,

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:39.700
who established the Second Dynasty.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:41.860
Internal strife and a lack of

00:13:41.860 --> 00:13:44.860
or misunderstanding over records

00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:48.330
ruined the Second Dynasty, 2,890 to 2,670 BCE.

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:53.680
None of the Second Dynasty monarchs have reliable dates,

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:55.450
and several of the king's names

00:13:55.450 --> 00:13:58.510
appear to be repeats of earlier rulers.

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:02.260
Hotepsekhemwy, which means two powerful ones at peace,

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:05.020
is a prime illustration of this issue.

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:08.050
Because of his name, it would seem that he came to power

00:14:08.050 --> 00:14:09.730
after subduing the princes

00:14:09.730 --> 00:14:12.070
who fought for the throne after Qa'a,

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:15.580
but his name is inscribed on the entrance to Qa'a's tomb,

00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:18.130
implying that he was the ruler responsible

00:14:18.130 --> 00:14:21.790
for burying Qa'a, and he already had that name

00:14:21.790 --> 00:14:24.400
before the succession war broke out.

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:27.280
Hotepsekhemwy is credited with bringing peace

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:29.980
to Egypt upon his ascension to the throne,

00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:31.540
although a brief one.

00:14:31.540 --> 00:14:34.690
Instability and rebellion marked his reign.

00:14:34.690 --> 00:14:36.610
Raneb, also known as Nebra,

00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:39.760
was the first to link his name to that of the gods,

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:44.440
and so create a bond between the monarch and the divine.

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:48.490
There is no reasonable explanation for Peribsen's decision.

00:14:48.490 --> 00:14:52.060
Early academics claimed he was the first monotheist

00:14:52.060 --> 00:14:55.210
who declared Seth to be the sole deity.

00:14:55.210 --> 00:14:57.250
But evidence of his reign's devotion

00:14:57.250 --> 00:14:59.770
to various gods disprove this,

00:14:59.770 --> 00:15:02.560
because his name is only found in Upper Egypt.

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:05.260
It's possible that he opted to ally with Seth

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:08.200
for political reasons, to distinguish himself

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:11.080
from the Horus religion of Lower Egypt.

00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:14.410
For whatever reason, he is regarded as a good monarch

00:15:14.410 --> 00:15:17.950
because commerce, the economy, religious practice,

00:15:17.950 --> 00:15:21.130
and the arts all thrived during his reign.

00:15:21.130 --> 00:15:25.450
Peribsen was replaced Khasekhemwy, probably his son,

00:15:25.450 --> 00:15:28.657
who continued his predecessor's construction projects

00:15:28.657 --> 00:15:31.600
and is believed to have brought Egypt's two regions

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:33.880
back under central control,

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:36.340
or at least reinforced unification.

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:38.650
His most famous works include the statues

00:15:38.650 --> 00:15:41.080
at Hierakonpolis and Abydos,

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:44.323
as well as his role as the father of Pharaoh Djoser.

00:15:49.331 --> 00:15:52.164
(dramatic music)

00:15:58.415 --> 00:16:02.020
The Egyptian Third Dynasty starts with King Djoser,

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:04.960
best known for his Step Pyramid at Saqqara.

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:06.910
Manetho's timeline is hazy on

00:16:06.910 --> 00:16:08.770
who Sanakht was when he governed

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:12.130
in the Third Dynasty and even his name.

00:16:12.130 --> 00:16:16.240
Sanakht's name is only known from the Abydos monarch list,

00:16:16.240 --> 00:16:19.510
the Turin Papyrus, and two reliefs discovered

00:16:19.510 --> 00:16:23.050
in the mastaba tomb, number K2 at Beit Khallaf.

00:16:23.050 --> 00:16:25.840
Djoser erected so many monuments

00:16:25.840 --> 00:16:27.850
that historians have long assumed

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:31.120
his tenure extended at least 20 years.

00:16:31.120 --> 00:16:33.790
He started military campaigns to Sinai,

00:16:33.790 --> 00:16:35.830
and kept Egyptian unity,

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:37.900
resulting in the stability required

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:41.920
for his construction projects and the growth of the arts.

00:16:41.920 --> 00:16:43.960
Djoser's Step Pyramid at Saqqara

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:46.900
is Egypt's first recognized pyramid,

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:51.010
which was designed by his architect and vizier Imhotep.

00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:55.060
Imhotep was a vizier, sage, architect, astrologer,

00:16:55.060 --> 00:16:57.490
and chief minister under Djoser,

00:16:57.490 --> 00:17:00.640
the second Pharaoh of Egypt's Third Dynasty,

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:02.680
who was later deified and worshiped

00:17:02.680 --> 00:17:06.340
as the God of medicine in Egypt and Greece,

00:17:06.340 --> 00:17:07.600
where he was associated

00:17:07.600 --> 00:17:10.870
with the Greek deity of medicine Asclepius.

00:17:10.870 --> 00:17:12.370
He is thought to have designed

00:17:12.370 --> 00:17:15.940
the Step Pyramid in Memphis' Saqqara Necropolis.

00:17:15.940 --> 00:17:18.040
This pyramid, which has six steps,

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:21.550
is the world's oldest surviving stone monument.

00:17:21.550 --> 00:17:24.130
An inscription carrying his name on a statue

00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:27.400
of Djoser uncovered near the Saqqara pyramid site

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:31.390
attests to Imhotep's high status in Djoser's court.

00:17:31.390 --> 00:17:33.310
The inscription includes titles,

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:35.770
such as the leader of the sculptures

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:37.990
and the chief of the sears.

00:17:37.990 --> 00:17:40.900
Historical documents depicting Egyptian society

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:43.090
and medicine throughout the Old Kingdom

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:45.100
demonstrate that the main magician

00:17:45.100 --> 00:17:47.530
of the pharaoh's court frequently functioned

00:17:47.530 --> 00:17:49.660
as the nation's chief physician.

00:17:49.660 --> 00:17:53.200
The Step Pyramid started as a basic mastaba monument,

00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:55.690
with a flat top and sloping sides,

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:59.050
similar to many previous dynasties' tombs.

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:01.570
The architect Imhotep, on the other hand,

00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:05.260
had bigger plans for his king's eternal dwelling.

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:08.260
The Step Pyramid is a succession of mastabas

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:10.240
piled on top of each other,

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:13.000
each step slightly smaller than the one beneath

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.400
to create a pyramid shape.

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:18.070
Earlier mastabas were made of clay bricks,

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:20.620
but the Step Pyramid was made of stone slabs

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:24.220
with carved motifs of trees and reeds on them.

00:18:24.220 --> 00:18:28.300
When finished, the Step Pyramid stood 62 meters tall,

00:18:28.300 --> 00:18:31.000
making it the tallest building of its period.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.610
To deter robbers and secure the king's corpse

00:18:33.610 --> 00:18:36.820
in burial goods, the real chambers of the tomb

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:39.040
were dug beneath the foundation

00:18:39.040 --> 00:18:43.240
as a maze of passageways with rooms off the hallways.

00:18:43.240 --> 00:18:45.670
However, this strategy did not work

00:18:45.670 --> 00:18:48.790
because the tomb was robbed of all of its valuables,

00:18:48.790 --> 00:18:52.090
including the king's corpse, in antiquity.

00:18:52.090 --> 00:18:55.090
Only his foot was discovered in the tomb.

00:18:55.090 --> 00:18:57.280
Nonetheless, the Step Pyramid's design

00:18:57.280 --> 00:18:59.770
and building epitomized the genius

00:18:59.770 --> 00:19:02.680
and vision of the Third Dynasty builders,

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:05.140
who would later raise the Buried Pyramid

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:06.730
and the Layer Pyramid,

00:19:06.730 --> 00:19:09.910
among many other structures and sanctuaries.

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:13.330
These early visionaries established the foundations

00:19:13.330 --> 00:19:17.260
for the later true pyramids of the Fourth Dynasty,

00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:21.493
which have mesmerized and captivated people for millennia.

00:19:24.452 --> 00:19:27.202
(dramatic music)

00:19:37.313 --> 00:19:39.700
The Old Kingdom of Egypt is also known

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:41.440
as the Age of the Pyramids

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:44.170
or the Age of the Pyramid Builders

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:47.080
because it contains the great Fourth Dynasty,

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:49.330
during which King Sneferu mastered

00:19:49.330 --> 00:19:51.700
the craft of pyramid construction,

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:53.710
and the Pyramids of Giza were built

00:19:53.710 --> 00:19:57.070
under the reigns of Khufu, Khafre and Menkaure.

00:19:57.070 --> 00:19:59.380
The historical documents of this time,

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:03.430
the Fourth to Sixth Dynasties of Egypt, are sparse,

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:06.220
and historians consider the history of the era

00:20:06.220 --> 00:20:08.920
as literally written in stone,

00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:11.740
and mainly architectural in that academics

00:20:11.740 --> 00:20:13.510
have been able to build a history

00:20:13.510 --> 00:20:16.180
through the statues and their inscriptions.

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:18.940
The pyramids themselves provide little information

00:20:18.940 --> 00:20:22.780
about their architects, but adjacent funerary shrines

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:25.000
and stelae provide the king's names

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.220
and other significant information.

00:20:27.220 --> 00:20:30.430
In addition, carvings in stone discovered elsewhere

00:20:30.430 --> 00:20:33.430
during the period document different events

00:20:33.430 --> 00:20:35.470
and the dates on which they happened.

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:39.580
Lastly, the mausoleum of the Fifth Dynasty's last monarch,

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:43.240
Unas, contained the first pyramid texts,

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:46.510
detailed drawings and writings inside the tomb

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:50.050
that cast light on the religious views of the period.

00:20:50.050 --> 00:20:51.880
During the Old Kingdom of Egypt,

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:53.830
the elites standardized art,

00:20:53.830 --> 00:20:56.110
and figures were produced uniformly

00:20:56.110 --> 00:20:59.170
to reflect the tastes of Memphis, the capital.

00:20:59.170 --> 00:21:00.400
Although other art forms,

00:21:00.400 --> 00:21:02.080
such as painting and literature

00:21:02.080 --> 00:21:04.510
exhibit more skill in the Old Kingdom,

00:21:04.510 --> 00:21:06.970
statues from the late Early Dynastic

00:21:06.970 --> 00:21:10.510
and early Old Kingdom periods are very comparable.

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:13.030
The Old Kingdom's most famous works of art

00:21:13.030 --> 00:21:14.710
are the Pyramids of Giza

00:21:14.710 --> 00:21:16.720
and the Great Sphinx of Giza,

00:21:16.720 --> 00:21:18.760
both of which remain today.

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:20.950
Although smaller structures were crafted

00:21:20.950 --> 00:21:23.200
with the same precision and beauty.

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:26.050
In reality, Egyptians placed great importance

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:30.370
on Old Kingdom art and architecture in later ages.

00:21:30.370 --> 00:21:32.950
Although all levels of society may have shared

00:21:32.950 --> 00:21:34.840
the same religious systems,

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:38.650
social inequality persisted even after death.

00:21:38.650 --> 00:21:40.390
The only significant impediment

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:44.530
to reaching an afterlife was being buried outside of Egypt.

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:46.900
Egyptians thought that to be reborn,

00:21:46.900 --> 00:21:49.270
they needed to be buried in Egypt.

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:51.700
If they died abroad, their relatives went

00:21:51.700 --> 00:21:55.750
to tremendous pains to bring their bodies back for burial,

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:59.050
so those correct funerary rituals could be performed,

00:21:59.050 --> 00:22:01.600
and they could be buried in their native land,

00:22:01.600 --> 00:22:04.690
allowing them to enter the afterlife.

00:22:04.690 --> 00:22:06.220
To coordinate the labor force

00:22:06.220 --> 00:22:08.200
that constructed the Pyramids at Giza

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:10.270
and elsewhere during this time,

00:22:10.270 --> 00:22:13.660
unprecedented bureaucratic efficiency was needed,

00:22:13.660 --> 00:22:15.880
and this bureaucracy could only function

00:22:15.880 --> 00:22:18.430
under a powerful central authority.

00:22:18.430 --> 00:22:19.840
At the top of the pyramid

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:23.860
that represented Egyptian society, the monarch stood.

00:22:23.860 --> 00:22:27.760
He was granted ownership of all of Egypt by the gods,

00:22:27.760 --> 00:22:29.320
at least in theory.

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:31.390
The literate and illiterate classes

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:34.120
were divided in the Egyptian social structure.

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:36.790
The literate class was the ruling class.

00:22:36.790 --> 00:22:39.970
They were a small fraction of the population,

00:22:39.970 --> 00:22:41.560
but they were the main criteria

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:45.040
for determining the character of ancient Egyptian society

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:47.890
and everything we knew about the civilization.

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:50.560
Individuals were frequently more important

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:52.390
than the positions they held.

00:22:52.390 --> 00:22:54.790
As a result, while the king established

00:22:54.790 --> 00:22:56.830
the scope of bureaucratic power,

00:22:56.830 --> 00:23:00.190
effective administration was ultimately dependent

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:03.160
on the same pool of literal aristocrats,

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:05.620
without whom the king could not govern,

00:23:05.620 --> 00:23:08.140
and we'll state some of them as follows.

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:11.380
Because an Egyptian king could not personally control

00:23:11.380 --> 00:23:13.540
every area of society,

00:23:13.540 --> 00:23:15.670
the role of the vizier was established

00:23:15.670 --> 00:23:18.640
as early as the Early Dynastic Period.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:20.680
The vizier, who can be assimilated

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:23.080
into a form of prime minister,

00:23:23.080 --> 00:23:26.350
assigned responsibility to other members of the court,

00:23:26.350 --> 00:23:28.750
sent communications through scribes,

00:23:28.750 --> 00:23:32.320
and managed the military, regional governor's activities,

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:33.790
public works projects

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:36.820
and tax collections, among other things.

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:39.520
Huni, the last king of the Third Dynasty

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:41.380
was a long thought to have initiated

00:23:41.380 --> 00:23:43.090
the massive building projects

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:46.720
of the Old Kingdom by constructing the Meidum Pyramid.

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:49.750
But credit for the Meidum Pyramid goes to Sneferu,

00:23:49.750 --> 00:23:51.910
the first king of the Fourth Dynasty

00:23:51.910 --> 00:23:55.540
who may have been Huni's son by one of his minor queens.

00:23:55.540 --> 00:23:58.990
Sneferu began the Old Kingdom's golden era,

00:23:58.990 --> 00:24:00.880
with his most noteworthy achievements

00:24:00.880 --> 00:24:04.510
being the two pyramids constructed for him at Dahshur.

00:24:04.510 --> 00:24:07.480
Sneferu started his work with the pyramid at Meidum,

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:10.750
known as the false pyramid due to its shape.

00:24:10.750 --> 00:24:13.570
It resembles a tower more than a pyramid,

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:15.850
and its exterior casing is surrounded

00:24:15.850 --> 00:24:18.220
by a massive mound of gravel.

00:24:18.220 --> 00:24:22.090
The pyramid of Meidum was Egypt's first real pyramid,

00:24:22.090 --> 00:24:24.100
but it did not last.

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:26.200
This is because changes were made

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:28.720
to Imhotep's initial pyramid design,

00:24:28.720 --> 00:24:31.570
causing the exterior casing to sit on sand

00:24:31.570 --> 00:24:34.180
rather than rock, causing it to fall.

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:36.190
The crooked period and the Red Pyramid

00:24:36.190 --> 00:24:38.530
are Sneferu's structures at Dahshur,

00:24:38.530 --> 00:24:40.210
or North Pyramid.

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:42.490
The Bend Pyramid gets its name from the fact

00:24:42.490 --> 00:24:45.430
that it rises at a 55 degree angle,

00:24:45.430 --> 00:24:49.870
and then changes to a 43 degree angle of smaller stones,

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:52.690
giving the impression of bending in towards the summit.

00:24:52.690 --> 00:24:55.060
The workers had finished the base and sides

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:59.380
before recognizing that a 55 degree angle was too steep,

00:24:59.380 --> 00:25:01.690
and changing their plan to conclude the job

00:25:01.690 --> 00:25:02.980
as best they could.

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:05.260
Sneferu appears to have grasped the issue

00:25:05.260 --> 00:25:07.840
and went on to construct his third pyramid.

00:25:07.840 --> 00:25:10.210
Sneferu appears to have been a ruler

00:25:10.210 --> 00:25:12.670
unafraid of loss or sorrow.

00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:13.990
When the Bent Pyramid failed

00:25:13.990 --> 00:25:17.260
to satisfy his standards, he simply began over.

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:19.270
The Red Pyramid, named after the use

00:25:19.270 --> 00:25:21.490
of reddish limestone in its building,

00:25:21.490 --> 00:25:25.270
was constructed on a firm foundation for better stability,

00:25:25.270 --> 00:25:28.240
and rose at a 43 degree inclination.

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:31.210
The Red Pyramid, 105 meters tall,

00:25:31.210 --> 00:25:34.900
was Egypt's first effective real pyramid.

00:25:34.900 --> 00:25:37.870
It was originally encased in white limestone,

00:25:37.870 --> 00:25:40.000
as were the other later pyramids,

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.890
which crumbled away over time

00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:43.450
and were collected by locals

00:25:43.450 --> 00:25:45.910
for other construction projects.

00:25:45.910 --> 00:25:49.240
Following in the footsteps of Djoser's complex at Saqqara,

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:51.580
Sneferu had mortuary temples

00:25:51.580 --> 00:25:54.760
and the other structures built around his pyramids,

00:25:54.760 --> 00:25:57.640
with priests overseeing day-to-day activities

00:25:57.640 --> 00:25:59.830
once the Red Pyramid was finished.

00:25:59.830 --> 00:26:03.100
All of this points to the stability of his rule,

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:06.790
which he bequeathed to his son Khufu when he died.

00:26:06.790 --> 00:26:10.690
The ancient Greek authors referred to Khufu as Cheops,

00:26:10.690 --> 00:26:14.200
and he's best known for his Great Pyramid at Giza.

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:17.140
In their works, the Greek portrayed him as a tyrant

00:26:17.140 --> 00:26:18.370
who oppressed the people

00:26:18.370 --> 00:26:21.610
and compelled them to labor for him against their will.

00:26:21.610 --> 00:26:23.770
This perception may have been created

00:26:23.770 --> 00:26:26.920
by the tales contained in the Westcar Papyrus,

00:26:26.920 --> 00:26:29.410
a compilation of four stories written about

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:31.360
the kings of the Fourth Dynasty,

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:36.360
and found by Henry Westcar in around 1824 CE.

00:26:36.580 --> 00:26:40.660
The papyrus contains four tales recounted by Khufu's sons,

00:26:40.660 --> 00:26:44.290
including one in which King Khufu summons a sorcerer,

00:26:44.290 --> 00:26:46.180
who claims to be able to reconnect

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:48.700
a decapitated head to a body.

00:26:48.700 --> 00:26:51.100
And some academics read his actions

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:55.450
in requesting a demonstration as malicious or careless.

00:26:55.450 --> 00:26:57.130
During the reign of Khufu,

00:26:57.130 --> 00:27:00.040
Egypt became even wealthier as a result

00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:03.610
of his military battles against Nubia and Libya,

00:27:03.610 --> 00:27:05.530
as well as his lucrative trade deals

00:27:05.530 --> 00:27:07.480
with cities such as Byblos.

00:27:07.480 --> 00:27:10.750
He also invested in agricultural innovations

00:27:10.750 --> 00:27:13.480
to improve the livelihoods of his people.

00:27:13.480 --> 00:27:16.750
During his reign, the world's first documented

00:27:16.750 --> 00:27:19.720
dam was constructed in Wadi Garawi,

00:27:19.720 --> 00:27:22.270
a mountain range west of modern Helwan.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:25.330
This dam improved water availability for farms

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:26.560
and others in the town.

00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:28.960
The Great Pyramid of Giza is the final

00:27:28.960 --> 00:27:32.110
of the ancient Seven Wonders of the World,

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:35.500
and a distinguishing emblem of Egypt.

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:37.870
It is situated on the Giza Plateau,

00:27:37.870 --> 00:27:40.000
near the modern city of Cairo,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:44.440
and was constructed over 20 years during the rule of Khufu.

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:46.870
Although many hypotheses exist

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:49.270
regarding the pyramid's purpose,

00:27:49.270 --> 00:27:51.820
the most generally acknowledged idea

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:54.550
is that it was built as a tomb for the king.

00:27:54.550 --> 00:27:56.380
However, how it was constructed

00:27:56.380 --> 00:27:58.990
remains a mystery to this day.

00:27:58.990 --> 00:28:01.570
Historians continue to dispute the idea

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:04.390
of ramps going around the outside of the building

00:28:04.390 --> 00:28:07.210
to move the blocks into position.

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:10.450
These theories persist, despite a growing body

00:28:10.450 --> 00:28:13.150
of evidence proving that the pyramid was constructed

00:28:13.150 --> 00:28:16.420
by the ancient Egyptians using technical means

00:28:16.420 --> 00:28:19.300
that were most likely so common to them

00:28:19.300 --> 00:28:22.060
that they felt no need to document them.

00:28:22.060 --> 00:28:23.950
Nonetheless, the complexity

00:28:23.950 --> 00:28:27.400
of the interior passages, shafts and chambers,

00:28:27.400 --> 00:28:29.890
as well as the nearby Osiris Shaft,

00:28:29.890 --> 00:28:33.850
encourages the persistence of these fringe theories,

00:28:33.850 --> 00:28:37.510
as does the mystery of how the pyramid was built at all,

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:40.810
and its orientation to cardinal points.

00:28:40.810 --> 00:28:42.910
A prominent figure during that time

00:28:42.910 --> 00:28:45.850
called Hemiunu was the vizier during the reign

00:28:45.850 --> 00:28:48.160
of Khufu in the Fourth Dynasty

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:50.440
and one of the king's relatives.

00:28:50.440 --> 00:28:53.440
He was in charge of building his Great Pyramid

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:56.440
and keeping an eye over its construction works,

00:28:56.440 --> 00:28:59.320
and he was buried near Khufu's pyramid.

00:28:59.320 --> 00:29:00.970
The construction work of the pyramid

00:29:00.970 --> 00:29:04.510
was done by expert and unskilled laborers

00:29:04.510 --> 00:29:06.850
employed by the state for the job.

00:29:06.850 --> 00:29:09.520
These employees either offered to pay off a debt,

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:13.210
performed community service, or were paid for their time.

00:29:13.210 --> 00:29:15.280
The annual inundation of the Nile River

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:17.680
was important for Egyptian survival

00:29:17.680 --> 00:29:20.590
because it distributed rich soil from the river bank

00:29:20.590 --> 00:29:23.350
all across the shore's farmlands.

00:29:23.350 --> 00:29:26.140
However, it also made farming those lands

00:29:26.140 --> 00:29:28.630
impossible during the flood.

00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:31.120
During these times, the government supplied work

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:34.510
for farms by constructing large monuments.

00:29:34.510 --> 00:29:36.040
These were the individuals

00:29:36.040 --> 00:29:40.510
who performed the real physical labor of moving stones,

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:43.810
elevating obelisks, constructing temples,

00:29:43.810 --> 00:29:47.230
and constructing the pyramids that continue to amaze

00:29:47.230 --> 00:29:49.333
and motivate people today.

00:29:51.670 --> 00:29:53.890
Khufu was replaced by a family member

00:29:53.890 --> 00:29:58.030
outside the legal line called Djedefre after his death.

00:29:58.030 --> 00:30:00.160
Djedefre was Khufu's son,

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:03.490
but he did not appear to be his designated heir.

00:30:03.490 --> 00:30:05.470
Some scholars believe Djedefre built

00:30:05.470 --> 00:30:07.270
the Great Sphinx of Giza,

00:30:07.270 --> 00:30:09.070
while others believed Khafre,

00:30:09.070 --> 00:30:11.500
his sibling and successor built it.

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:15.460
The Sphinx is the world's biggest monolithic monument,

00:30:15.460 --> 00:30:18.280
showing a recumbent lion's torso

00:30:18.280 --> 00:30:20.530
with a king's head and visage.

00:30:20.530 --> 00:30:22.480
Historically, this king's visage

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:24.580
has been identified as Khafre's,

00:30:24.580 --> 00:30:27.880
but Dobrev and others believe it's Khufu's.

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:30.430
It appears to have been constructed by Khafre

00:30:30.430 --> 00:30:34.450
because it is exactly in line with his pyramid complex,

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:38.530
and the Sphinx's face resembles Khafre more than Khufu.

00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:42.070
Khafre's pyramid is the second largest in Giza,

00:30:42.070 --> 00:30:45.640
and his complex is almost as big as his father's.

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:47.620
Little is known about his rule.

00:30:47.620 --> 00:30:49.450
According to Egyptian texts,

00:30:49.450 --> 00:30:51.370
he continued his father's policies

00:30:51.370 --> 00:30:54.220
and government model by concentrating power

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:56.800
in the hands of his closest family members,

00:30:56.800 --> 00:31:01.090
and exerting strict control over policies and laws.

00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:02.920
Following Khafre's demise,

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:06.250
succession was temporarily disrupted again

00:31:06.250 --> 00:31:09.760
when Baka, Djedefre's son, took the throne.

00:31:09.760 --> 00:31:11.920
He did not even rule for a year

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:15.940
before Menkaure, Khafre's son, took over as monarch.

00:31:15.940 --> 00:31:19.660
Both the Greeks and the Egyptian writings praise Menkaure.

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:22.420
Menkaure, like his father and grandpa before him,

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:26.560
started construction on his Giza pyramid and shrine complex.

00:31:26.560 --> 00:31:28.300
Menkaure's pyramid and complex

00:31:28.300 --> 00:31:29.980
are smaller than the other two,

00:31:29.980 --> 00:31:32.200
which represent a significant development

00:31:32.200 --> 00:31:34.360
in the history of the Old Kingdom,

00:31:34.360 --> 00:31:37.300
and one of the causes of its collapse.

00:31:37.300 --> 00:31:39.430
The resources required to construct

00:31:39.430 --> 00:31:42.370
the Great Pyramid were no longer accessible

00:31:42.370 --> 00:31:44.200
during Menkaure's period,

00:31:44.200 --> 00:31:46.030
but he did his best to establish

00:31:46.030 --> 00:31:49.870
an everlasting residence on par with his fathers'

00:31:49.870 --> 00:31:51.490
and grandfathers'.

00:31:51.490 --> 00:31:55.180
Khuenre, Menkaure's son and designated successor

00:31:55.180 --> 00:31:58.060
perished while this pyramid was being constructed,

00:31:58.060 --> 00:32:00.370
upsetting the dynastic succession,

00:32:00.370 --> 00:32:04.480
and Menkaure died before the pyramid complex was finished.

00:32:04.480 --> 00:32:07.660
Despite reigning for 30 years, he was unable

00:32:07.660 --> 00:32:10.180
to finish the work of his predecessors,

00:32:10.180 --> 00:32:12.070
which many historians attribute

00:32:12.070 --> 00:32:15.250
to the dwindling resources at his disposal.

00:32:15.250 --> 00:32:17.680
Shepseskaf, Menkaure's successor,

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:19.930
finished Menkaure's structure at Giza,

00:32:19.930 --> 00:32:24.160
but was buried in a relatively modest mastaba at Saqqara.

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:25.870
As previously stated,

00:32:25.870 --> 00:32:28.720
the monarchs diverted immense resources

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:31.480
to their funerary structures and buildings,

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:33.430
but these temples and sanctuaries

00:32:33.430 --> 00:32:35.230
were increasingly under the authority

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:38.620
of the priests who managed them rather than the king.

00:32:38.620 --> 00:32:42.790
Although the Giza Plateau is now an old sand swept location

00:32:42.790 --> 00:32:44.860
on the outskirts of Cairo,

00:32:44.860 --> 00:32:47.050
it was a city of the deceased,

00:32:47.050 --> 00:32:49.810
inhabited by the living who tended to it

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:51.490
during Menkaure's time.

00:32:51.490 --> 00:32:54.280
Giza had priests houses, shrines,

00:32:54.280 --> 00:32:58.120
worker accommodations, stores, factories, breweries,

00:32:58.120 --> 00:33:01.900
and all the amenities of a small metropolis.

00:33:01.900 --> 00:33:05.470
The civilian life in ancient Egypt was very active.

00:33:05.470 --> 00:33:08.500
The lowest social class consisted of peasant farmers

00:33:08.500 --> 00:33:11.230
who did not own the land on which they worked on

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:13.330
or the houses in which they resided.

00:33:13.330 --> 00:33:15.490
The monarch, members of the court,

00:33:15.490 --> 00:33:18.310
nomarchs and priests owned the land.

00:33:18.310 --> 00:33:20.387
To begin the day, peasants would say,

00:33:20.387 --> 00:33:22.420
"Let us work for the nobility."

00:33:22.420 --> 00:33:25.510
Peasants were virtually always farmers,

00:33:25.510 --> 00:33:28.240
regardless of what other trade they practiced.

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:30.550
They cultivated and harvested their crops,

00:33:30.550 --> 00:33:32.470
giving the majority to the landowner,

00:33:32.470 --> 00:33:34.690
while keeping part for themselves.

00:33:34.690 --> 00:33:36.490
Most had private gardens,

00:33:36.490 --> 00:33:37.870
which the ladies maintained

00:33:37.870 --> 00:33:39.970
while the men worked in the fields.

00:33:39.970 --> 00:33:41.740
The lowest stratum of society

00:33:41.740 --> 00:33:44.410
created the items utilized in commerce,

00:33:44.410 --> 00:33:47.470
allowing the civilization as a whole to survive.

00:33:47.470 --> 00:33:50.170
These peasants were also part of the workforce

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:53.590
that erected Egypt's pyramids and other monuments.

00:33:53.590 --> 00:33:55.840
When the Nile River's banks overflowed,

00:33:55.840 --> 00:33:57.640
farming became difficult,

00:33:57.640 --> 00:34:00.940
and the men and women went to work on the king's projects.

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:03.400
This labor was always rewarded,

00:34:03.400 --> 00:34:05.560
and no literary or physical evidence

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:07.060
supports the assertion that

00:34:07.060 --> 00:34:09.010
any of Egypt's major monuments

00:34:09.010 --> 00:34:11.410
were erected by slave labor.

00:34:11.410 --> 00:34:13.570
Work building monuments like the pyramid

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:17.440
and associated burial complexes, temples and obelisks

00:34:17.440 --> 00:34:20.350
provided the peasantry with the sole possibility

00:34:20.350 --> 00:34:22.060
of upward mobility.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:23.980
Skilled painters and engravers

00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:27.340
in particular were in high demand in Egypt,

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:29.710
and were paid more than unskilled laborers

00:34:29.710 --> 00:34:31.390
who merely hauled the stones

00:34:31.390 --> 00:34:34.150
for the construction from one location to another.

00:34:34.150 --> 00:34:36.790
Peasant farmers might also raise their status

00:34:36.790 --> 00:34:38.050
by learning a craft

00:34:38.050 --> 00:34:40.540
and producing the vases, bowls, plates

00:34:40.540 --> 00:34:42.670
and other ceramics that people need.

00:34:42.670 --> 00:34:46.390
Skilled carpenters could make a fortune by making tables,

00:34:46.390 --> 00:34:49.540
desks, chairs, beds and storage chests,

00:34:49.540 --> 00:34:50.920
while painters were needed

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:52.960
to decorate upper class dwellings,

00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:55.450
castles, tombs and monuments.

00:34:55.450 --> 00:34:58.330
Brewers were likewise held in high regard,

00:34:58.330 --> 00:35:01.600
and breweries were occasionally controlled by women.

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:04.060
They appear to have been operated on by females

00:35:04.060 --> 00:35:05.950
in early Egyptian history.

00:35:05.950 --> 00:35:09.220
Beer was the most popular beverage in ancient Egypt,

00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:12.880
and it was commonly utilized as a kind of recompense.

00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:13.990
Three times a day,

00:35:13.990 --> 00:35:17.560
workers on the Giza Plateau were given a beer ration.

00:35:17.560 --> 00:35:19.540
The deity Osiris was said to have

00:35:19.540 --> 00:35:21.610
provided the drink to the people,

00:35:21.610 --> 00:35:25.060
and breweries were overseen by the goddess Tjenenyet.

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:26.830
Marriages were more secular

00:35:26.830 --> 00:35:28.720
than religious in ancient Egypt.

00:35:28.720 --> 00:35:30.760
The parents planned the majority of weddings

00:35:30.760 --> 00:35:32.560
in any of the classes.

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:35.440
Girls were often married at the age of 12,

00:35:35.440 --> 00:35:37.810
and boys at the age of 15.

00:35:37.810 --> 00:35:40.240
Royal offspring were frequently promised

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:43.600
to foreign monarchs as babies to seal treaties.

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:47.050
The ancient Egyptians' lives were not all labor.

00:35:47.050 --> 00:35:49.030
They found plenty of time to have fun

00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:50.950
by participating in sports,

00:35:50.950 --> 00:35:53.170
board games and other activities.

00:35:53.170 --> 00:35:55.990
Hockey, handball, archery, swimming,

00:35:55.990 --> 00:35:58.570
tug of war, gymnastics, rowing,

00:35:58.570 --> 00:36:01.330
and a sport known as water jousting,

00:36:01.330 --> 00:36:03.820
which was a sea battle played in small boats

00:36:03.820 --> 00:36:06.340
on the Nile River, in which a jouster

00:36:06.340 --> 00:36:08.380
tried to knock the other out of his boat,

00:36:08.380 --> 00:36:11.020
while the second team member maneuvered the craft

00:36:11.020 --> 00:36:13.990
were all ancient Egyptian sports.

00:36:13.990 --> 00:36:15.730
The festivals of ancient Egypt

00:36:15.730 --> 00:36:18.670
were individually distinct in their own right,

00:36:18.670 --> 00:36:20.620
depending on the nature of the occasion,

00:36:20.620 --> 00:36:23.170
but they all had one thing in common,

00:36:23.170 --> 00:36:25.030
drinking and feasting.

00:36:25.030 --> 00:36:28.030
The Egyptian diet consisted mostly of grains,

00:36:28.030 --> 00:36:30.130
wheat, and vegetables.

00:36:30.130 --> 00:36:32.710
The meat was incredibly expensive,

00:36:32.710 --> 00:36:35.050
and only royalty could afford it.

00:36:35.050 --> 00:36:38.530
The Fourth Dynasty ended with Shepseskaf's brief reign,

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:41.590
and the fifth started with much less hope.

00:36:41.590 --> 00:36:45.070
The Fifth Dynasty is known as the Sun King's Dynasty

00:36:45.070 --> 00:36:46.930
because so many of their titles

00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:51.220
contain the name of the deity Ra, usually given as RE.

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:53.020
The first three of these rulers,

00:36:53.020 --> 00:36:55.390
Userkaf, Sahure and Kakai

00:36:55.390 --> 00:36:57.010
would later be memorialized

00:36:57.010 --> 00:37:01.150
as divinely chosen in the Westcar Papyrus tale

00:37:01.150 --> 00:37:02.920
the birth of the kings.

00:37:02.920 --> 00:37:05.470
The dynasty starts with King Userkaf,

00:37:05.470 --> 00:37:07.330
but a lady called Khentkaus,

00:37:07.330 --> 00:37:09.580
most likely a daughter of Menkaure,

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:12.280
appears prominently in the Egyptian texts

00:37:12.280 --> 00:37:16.330
as mother of two kings of Upper and Lower Egypt,

00:37:16.330 --> 00:37:19.570
though it's unclear who those monarchs were.

00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:22.270
Her monument is the fourth pyramid at Giza,

00:37:22.270 --> 00:37:24.640
and she was a significant person.

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:26.620
Not much is known about her.

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:28.930
Userkaf is best renowned for his work

00:37:28.930 --> 00:37:31.690
on the Temple of the Sun in Abusir.

00:37:31.690 --> 00:37:35.110
This structure represents a significant divergence

00:37:35.110 --> 00:37:36.670
from the position of the monarch

00:37:36.670 --> 00:37:38.920
at the beginning of the Fourth Dynasty,

00:37:38.920 --> 00:37:41.710
and the beginning of the end of Giza

00:37:41.710 --> 00:37:43.990
as the king's necropolis.

00:37:43.990 --> 00:37:46.570
The sun deity Ra was now venerated

00:37:46.570 --> 00:37:49.540
directly by the people through the priesthood,

00:37:49.540 --> 00:37:50.710
and the king's position

00:37:50.710 --> 00:37:54.460
as the God's primary representative was reduced.

00:37:54.460 --> 00:37:57.100
Userkaf's son Sahure replaced him

00:37:57.100 --> 00:37:59.530
and constructed his funerary complex

00:37:59.530 --> 00:38:02.470
at Abusir, near the Temple of the Sun.

00:38:02.470 --> 00:38:04.240
Sahure was a capable monarch

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:07.600
who led the first Egyptian expedition to Punt,

00:38:07.600 --> 00:38:10.240
and arranged significant trade treaties

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:11.740
with other countries.

00:38:11.740 --> 00:38:13.150
Punt, on the other hand,

00:38:13.150 --> 00:38:15.670
was one of his biggest accomplishments,

00:38:15.670 --> 00:38:17.920
as it became an important source

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:21.370
of many of Egypt's most valuable resources,

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:26.370
and in time was regarded as a legendary country of the gods.

00:38:26.877 --> 00:38:30.520
Sahure constructed his own temple to the sun in Abusir,

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:34.240
and was the first to use palmiform columns in the building,

00:38:34.240 --> 00:38:36.100
which would later become the norm

00:38:36.100 --> 00:38:38.710
for columns throughout Egypt.

00:38:38.710 --> 00:38:41.740
Sahure's war exploits and cautious resource management

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:44.140
enrichened the nation, as demonstrated

00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:47.680
by the intricate work done on his mortuary complex,

00:38:47.680 --> 00:38:49.780
and the inscriptions discovered.

00:38:49.780 --> 00:38:53.260
His son Neferirkare Kakai succeeded him.

00:38:53.260 --> 00:38:56.770
Inscriptions suggest he was a good king and well-regarded,

00:38:56.770 --> 00:38:59.170
but little is known of his tenure,

00:38:59.170 --> 00:39:00.550
except that the priesthood

00:39:00.550 --> 00:39:03.670
got even more dominant during his control.

00:39:03.670 --> 00:39:07.870
His son Neferefre succeeded him but perished young,

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:10.230
possibly around the age of 20.

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:13.192
He was followed by King Shepseskare.

00:39:13.192 --> 00:39:15.610
Nyuserre Ini succeeds him.

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:17.920
And the priests of Ra acquire

00:39:17.920 --> 00:39:20.860
even more authority during his rule.

00:39:20.860 --> 00:39:22.420
The bureaucracy of the temples

00:39:22.420 --> 00:39:25.060
and mortuary buildings grew as well,

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:27.340
putting a burden on royal coffers,

00:39:27.340 --> 00:39:30.454
which paid for sanctuary care and maintenance.

00:39:30.454 --> 00:39:32.680
Menkauhor Kaiu replaced him,

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:34.810
but little is known about his rule,

00:39:34.810 --> 00:39:37.450
other than the fact that he was the last monarch

00:39:37.450 --> 00:39:39.970
to construct a temple to the sun.

00:39:39.970 --> 00:39:41.727
Djedkare Isesi replaced him

00:39:41.727 --> 00:39:45.730
in the late 25th to mid 24th century BC.

00:39:45.730 --> 00:39:48.520
The roots of Djedkare Isesi are unclear.

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:51.370
He's not regarded as Menkauhor Kaiu's son,

00:39:51.370 --> 00:39:53.380
but he may be connected.

00:39:53.380 --> 00:39:55.000
To keep the economy stable,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.040
he reforms the administration

00:39:57.040 --> 00:40:00.130
and the clergy extensively during his rule.

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:02.950
Djedkare Isesi refused the customary practice

00:40:02.950 --> 00:40:05.470
of erecting a shrine to the sun deity,

00:40:05.470 --> 00:40:07.570
and decreased the number of clerics

00:40:07.570 --> 00:40:10.870
required to maintain funerary structures.

00:40:10.870 --> 00:40:14.260
He also arranged the second Punt expedition,

00:40:14.260 --> 00:40:18.160
which enriched Egypt and reinforced relations with Punt.

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:20.860
The most important element of Djedkare Isesi's reign,

00:40:20.860 --> 00:40:23.170
however, was the decentralization

00:40:23.170 --> 00:40:25.240
of the government in Memphis,

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:28.540
which gave local authorities more authority.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:31.750
Djedkare Isesi was replaced by his son Unas,

00:40:31.750 --> 00:40:34.450
the reign of whom is little documented.

00:40:34.450 --> 00:40:36.760
Unas was the first Egyptian king

00:40:36.760 --> 00:40:39.490
to have the interior of his tomb decorated

00:40:39.490 --> 00:40:44.020
and inscribed with what became known as the pyramid texts.

00:40:44.020 --> 00:40:45.940
These inscriptions depict the king

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:48.640
in communion with Ra and Osiris.

00:40:48.640 --> 00:40:52.270
The position of the king was already considerably reduced

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:54.130
when the Sixth Dynasty started.

00:40:54.130 --> 00:40:57.430
Local officials and bureaucrats built more elaborate tombs

00:40:57.430 --> 00:41:00.318
than nobles during the rule of the first monarch.

00:41:00.318 --> 00:41:01.151
Teti.

00:41:01.151 --> 00:41:03.670
Teti was killed by his bodyguards

00:41:03.670 --> 00:41:07.660
according to the third century BCE historian Manetho,

00:41:07.660 --> 00:41:11.710
an act that would've been inconceivable earlier.

00:41:11.710 --> 00:41:13.780
He was replaced by Userkare,

00:41:13.780 --> 00:41:17.230
who may have been involved in the assassination plan.

00:41:17.230 --> 00:41:19.060
His reign was brief,

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:22.150
and he was followed by Meryre Pepi I,

00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:24.610
during whom the nomarchs gained authority.

00:41:24.610 --> 00:41:26.470
By the end of Old Kingdom,

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:28.750
the political power had fragmented

00:41:28.750 --> 00:41:31.180
and the system was decentralized.

00:41:31.180 --> 00:41:34.630
The restoration of central power was a lengthy process

00:41:34.630 --> 00:41:37.690
that lasted well into the 12th Dynasty.

00:41:37.690 --> 00:41:40.000
Because of the breakdown of central power,

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.630
political authority passed into the hands of the nomarchs,

00:41:43.630 --> 00:41:45.940
who took complete control.

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:48.460
This pattern persisted during the reigns

00:41:48.460 --> 00:41:53.290
of Merenre Nemtyemsaf I, and Neferkare Pepi II,

00:41:53.290 --> 00:41:55.750
who ascended to the kingdom as a child

00:41:55.750 --> 00:41:57.940
and perished as an old man,

00:41:57.940 --> 00:42:02.350
signifying an incredible rule of nearly a century.

00:42:02.350 --> 00:42:04.840
During Pepe II's lengthy rule,

00:42:04.840 --> 00:42:07.510
the Old Kingdom gradually crumble.

00:42:07.510 --> 00:42:10.150
The increasing influence of provincial nomarchs

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:13.150
and the clergy eroded the central governments'

00:42:13.150 --> 00:42:14.920
and kings' authority.

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:18.880
Pepe II was followed by Merenre Nemtyemsaf II

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:20.800
with a very short reign.

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:23.230
And the dynasty ended with Netjerkare,

00:42:23.230 --> 00:42:27.010
who was identified by some scholars and Egyptologists

00:42:27.010 --> 00:42:29.080
as the Queen Nitocris

00:42:29.080 --> 00:42:32.200
from Herodotus's account of an Egyptian queen

00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:34.090
who avenges her brother's murder

00:42:34.090 --> 00:42:36.730
by drowning his killers at a banquet.

00:42:36.730 --> 00:42:40.360
Pepe II had outlived any heirs to the throne,

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:43.330
and appears to have been a pretty ineffective monarch

00:42:43.330 --> 00:42:44.800
in his final years.

00:42:44.800 --> 00:42:47.050
When drought caused famine in the country,

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:50.350
there was no effective central authority to react to it.

00:42:50.350 --> 00:42:53.260
The Old Kingdom terminated with the Sixth Dynasty

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:56.530
because no powerful ruler ascended to the throne

00:42:56.530 --> 00:42:57.850
to guide the people.

00:42:57.850 --> 00:43:00.370
Local authorities focused on their areas

00:43:00.370 --> 00:43:02.800
and lacked the means and motivation

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:04.810
to assist the rest of the nation.

00:43:04.810 --> 00:43:06.940
As the Sixth Dynasty died out,

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:08.680
Egypt gradually descended

00:43:08.680 --> 00:43:11.503
into the First Intermediate Period.

00:43:15.656 --> 00:43:18.156
(tense music)

00:43:23.201 --> 00:43:25.951
(dramatic music)

00:43:35.320 --> 00:43:38.860
The First Intermediate Period is marked primarily

00:43:38.860 --> 00:43:42.190
by a rise in the authority of provincial administrators

00:43:42.190 --> 00:43:43.990
of distinct areas,

00:43:43.990 --> 00:43:45.550
and a decline in the power

00:43:45.550 --> 00:43:48.070
of the central government at Memphis.

00:43:48.070 --> 00:43:49.930
The great structures of the Old Kingdom

00:43:49.930 --> 00:43:51.790
on the scale of Giza's pyramids

00:43:51.790 --> 00:43:53.440
were no longer constructed

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:55.600
within the First Intermediate Period

00:43:55.600 --> 00:43:58.210
because there was no strong central sovereign

00:43:58.210 --> 00:44:00.040
to order and pay for them,

00:44:00.040 --> 00:44:03.280
and no administration to coordinate the large workforce.

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:05.590
The cultural image that comes from a study

00:44:05.590 --> 00:44:09.970
of historical data does not support a chaotic dark era,

00:44:09.970 --> 00:44:12.790
but rather a different social and political model

00:44:12.790 --> 00:44:14.260
than what had come before.

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:16.330
There is some historical evidence

00:44:16.330 --> 00:44:19.660
for the claim of unrest and claimed disorder,

00:44:19.660 --> 00:44:21.280
which stems from the absence

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:24.040
of a single powerful central government.

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:25.600
The country's different regions

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:27.700
were essentially self-governing.

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:29.800
The dearth of information about the kings

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:31.480
of the Seventh and Eighth Dynasties

00:44:31.480 --> 00:44:33.970
attest to their ineffectiveness.

00:44:33.970 --> 00:44:36.430
Their identities and dates will be forgotten

00:44:36.430 --> 00:44:38.290
in Egyptian annals.

00:44:38.290 --> 00:44:40.780
The ancient city of Memphis was abandoned

00:44:40.780 --> 00:44:43.240
at some time by rulers who saw themselves

00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:46.150
as the heirs of the Old Kingdom kings.

00:44:46.150 --> 00:44:48.910
The rulers of the Ninth and Tenth Dynasties

00:44:48.910 --> 00:44:52.150
then seized Herakleopolis as their center

00:44:52.150 --> 00:44:55.917
and declared themselves Egypt's real kings.

00:44:55.917 --> 00:44:59.860
Intef, a Theben nomarch who bore the customary epithets

00:44:59.860 --> 00:45:02.530
of great overlord of the nomes

00:45:02.530 --> 00:45:04.870
and overseer of priests

00:45:04.870 --> 00:45:09.340
came to prominence in Thebes around 2125 BC,

00:45:09.340 --> 00:45:13.011
and opposed the authority of Herakleopolitan kings.

00:45:13.011 --> 00:45:16.900
Intef I established Egypt's 11th Dynasty,

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:20.380
and provided the push for the country's unity.

00:45:20.380 --> 00:45:21.610
During the Middle Kingdom,

00:45:21.610 --> 00:45:23.920
he was known as Intef the Mighty,

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:26.080
and a monument in his honor was erected

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:27.580
in the Temple of Karnak,

00:45:27.580 --> 00:45:30.910
and this was the way leading to the beginning

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:34.513
of a new era, which was the Middle Kingdom.

00:45:38.869 --> 00:45:42.036
(gentle upbeat music)

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:52.360
Although Mentuhotep II was known as the second menace

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:56.050
who united Egypt and ushered in the Middle Kingdom period,

00:45:56.050 --> 00:45:59.530
the road to that unity was laid out by Intef I

00:45:59.530 --> 00:46:01.300
and his successors.

00:46:01.300 --> 00:46:06.300
Mentuhotep I, approximately 2115 BCE,

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:08.680
followed Intef I's path

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:11.860
and conquered the neighboring nomes for Thebes,

00:46:11.860 --> 00:46:15.280
considerably increasing the city's stature and strength.

00:46:15.280 --> 00:46:18.880
His initiatives were carried on by his predecessors.

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:21.820
Mentuhotep II used these early victories

00:46:21.820 --> 00:46:24.280
to ultimately beat Herakleopolis

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:26.380
and then punish those nomes,

00:46:26.380 --> 00:46:29.290
who had stayed faithful to the old kings,

00:46:29.290 --> 00:46:32.050
while rewarding those who had honored Thebes.

00:46:32.050 --> 00:46:34.720
Mentuhotep II devoted his time

00:46:34.720 --> 00:46:37.210
after the process of unity to the ruling,

00:46:37.210 --> 00:46:40.765
military accomplishments and construction projects.

00:46:40.765 --> 00:46:44.433
Mentuhotep's successor, Mentuhotep III,

00:46:44.433 --> 00:46:48.940
reigned during 2010 to 1998 BCE,

00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:51.790
maintained and expanded his programs.

00:46:51.790 --> 00:46:53.440
He dispatched an army to Punt

00:46:53.440 --> 00:46:56.650
and strengthened the northern delta's borders.

00:46:56.650 --> 00:46:59.110
Mentuhotep IV replaced him.

00:46:59.110 --> 00:47:01.750
His entire seven year rule is silent,

00:47:01.750 --> 00:47:03.250
but he most likely continued

00:47:03.250 --> 00:47:05.740
his predecessor's policies effectively,

00:47:05.740 --> 00:47:07.810
because the nation is thriving

00:47:07.810 --> 00:47:10.780
when Amenemhat replaces him as monarch.

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:14.020
When Amenemhat was Mentuhotep IV's vizier

00:47:14.020 --> 00:47:16.390
and was sent with his mission to quarry stones

00:47:16.390 --> 00:47:19.600
for the king's project, he had an inscription made

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:22.510
of the extraordinary events he witnessed.

00:47:22.510 --> 00:47:25.240
First, a gazelle gave birth on the stone

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:28.030
selected for the king's sarcophagus top,

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:30.790
indicating that the stone had been chosen correctly

00:47:30.790 --> 00:47:33.850
because it was endowed with fecundity and life.

00:47:33.850 --> 00:47:36.730
Second, an unanticipated rainfall

00:47:36.730 --> 00:47:38.770
descended on the celebration,

00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:40.660
revealing a well big enough

00:47:40.660 --> 00:47:43.270
to water the entire gathering.

00:47:43.270 --> 00:47:45.970
This inscription was later interpreted to mean

00:47:45.970 --> 00:47:49.630
that Amenemhat was chosen by the gods to become king,

00:47:49.630 --> 00:47:53.380
as the gods that allowed him to experience miracles.

00:47:53.380 --> 00:47:57.550
Amenemhat I abandoned Thebes for unknown reasons

00:47:57.550 --> 00:48:01.090
and established his seat in court in Itjtawy,

00:48:01.090 --> 00:48:02.590
south of Memphis.

00:48:02.590 --> 00:48:04.930
Amenemhat I's successor,

00:48:04.930 --> 00:48:08.683
Senusret I, 1971 to 1926 BCE,

00:48:10.450 --> 00:48:12.910
improved the country's infrastructure

00:48:12.910 --> 00:48:16.330
and initiated the kinds of grand building projects

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:18.640
that had characterized the Old Kingdom,

00:48:18.640 --> 00:48:20.860
and represented the king's power,

00:48:20.860 --> 00:48:23.410
including a temple to Amun at Karnak,

00:48:23.410 --> 00:48:25.060
which sparked the construction

00:48:25.060 --> 00:48:27.640
of the Great Temple complex there.

00:48:27.640 --> 00:48:30.220
Amenemhat I had followed in the footsteps

00:48:30.220 --> 00:48:33.670
of Intef II and Mentuhotep II

00:48:33.670 --> 00:48:37.690
by restricting the authority of local nomarchs and priests,

00:48:37.690 --> 00:48:39.790
and giving power only to those

00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:41.530
most trusted in the family.

00:48:41.530 --> 00:48:44.830
Senusret I continued the same strategy.

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:48.220
The administration of the 12th Dynasty was so effective

00:48:48.220 --> 00:48:49.990
that unlike the Old Kingdom,

00:48:49.990 --> 00:48:52.630
it kept wealth centralized with the monarch,

00:48:52.630 --> 00:48:54.070
while allowing for the development

00:48:54.070 --> 00:48:57.040
and prosperity of individual regions,

00:48:57.040 --> 00:48:59.620
without allowing them to become too strong.

00:48:59.620 --> 00:49:02.410
The king governed all of Egypt,

00:49:02.410 --> 00:49:05.980
but specific officers were rewarded for their devotion.

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:09.040
The Egyptians developed various advanced ways

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:10.990
of irrigation systems,

00:49:10.990 --> 00:49:13.120
and to keep track of the water levels,

00:49:13.120 --> 00:49:15.970
they build nilometers to gauge the height of the flood

00:49:15.970 --> 00:49:19.150
and to determine the taxes levels supposed to be paid.

00:49:19.150 --> 00:49:22.150
Canals were dug to provide water to different areas

00:49:22.150 --> 00:49:25.600
when Senusret II decided to turn the Faiyum area

00:49:25.600 --> 00:49:27.880
into an agricultural center.

00:49:27.880 --> 00:49:30.550
He developed a specific irrigation system

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:33.850
with a dyke that transported water from Lake Moeris,

00:49:33.850 --> 00:49:37.240
which resulted in crop prosperity in the area.

00:49:37.240 --> 00:49:40.630
It was also behind the construction of the White Chapel,

00:49:40.630 --> 00:49:44.080
a building important to historians and academics

00:49:44.080 --> 00:49:45.520
because it contains a record

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:48.208
of all the nomes of the period.

00:49:48.208 --> 00:49:51.549
Senusret I was followed by Amenemhat II,

00:49:51.549 --> 00:49:56.549
1929 to 1895 BCE, who may have governed alongside him.

00:49:57.610 --> 00:50:01.930
The practice of coregency was unique to the Middle Kingdom,

00:50:01.930 --> 00:50:04.990
in which a younger man, the monarch's selected heir,

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:08.080
usually a son, would govern alongside the king

00:50:08.080 --> 00:50:09.460
to learn the position,

00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:12.460
and guarantee a seamless transfer of power.

00:50:12.460 --> 00:50:14.770
Scholars disagree on whether this practice

00:50:14.770 --> 00:50:18.580
was truly followed, though there is no question

00:50:18.580 --> 00:50:21.100
that it was followed by Amenemhat II

00:50:21.100 --> 00:50:24.683
and his successor Senusret II, 1897 to 1878 BCE.

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:29.470
Double dates for two rulers

00:50:29.470 --> 00:50:33.160
on official cartouches indicate coregency.

00:50:33.160 --> 00:50:35.830
Amenemhat II's reign is little known,

00:50:35.830 --> 00:50:39.310
but Senusret II is noted for his excellent ties

00:50:39.310 --> 00:50:41.110
with the regional nomarchs,

00:50:41.110 --> 00:50:43.660
and improved prosperity of the nation.

00:50:43.660 --> 00:50:46.930
It's worth noting that during Senusret II's rule,

00:50:46.930 --> 00:50:49.510
local officials thrived just as they had

00:50:49.510 --> 00:50:51.460
at the end of the Old Kingdom,

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:53.590
but this did not cause the kingdom

00:50:53.590 --> 00:50:56.140
the difficulties that it had previously.

00:50:56.140 --> 00:50:59.500
Senusret II was followed by Senusret III,

00:50:59.500 --> 00:51:03.190
1878 to 1860 BCE,

00:51:03.190 --> 00:51:06.100
the most potent monarch of the period,

00:51:06.100 --> 00:51:08.440
whose reign was so prosperous

00:51:08.440 --> 00:51:11.410
that he was deified during his lifetime.

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:13.120
His rule is characterized

00:51:13.120 --> 00:51:15.670
by military advancement into Nubia,

00:51:15.670 --> 00:51:19.499
as well as a rise in Egypt's riches and influence.

00:51:19.499 --> 00:51:23.560
Senusret III exemplified the Egyptian cultural value

00:51:23.560 --> 00:51:25.240
of military ability,

00:51:25.240 --> 00:51:29.130
and quick action was the pinnacle of the warrior king.

00:51:29.130 --> 00:51:33.400
He was thought to be unbeatable at the helm of his troops.

00:51:33.400 --> 00:51:37.090
His expeditions into Nubia widened Egypt's borders,

00:51:37.090 --> 00:51:38.980
and the fortifications he erected

00:51:38.980 --> 00:51:42.070
along the boundary facilitated commerce.

00:51:42.070 --> 00:51:45.400
He also conducted an expedition into Palestine,

00:51:45.400 --> 00:51:49.450
and as a result, trade ties with that area improved.

00:51:49.450 --> 00:51:53.020
And to control flood and direct irrigation waters,

00:51:53.020 --> 00:51:56.020
the ancient Egyptians built earth and stone barrages

00:51:56.020 --> 00:51:59.020
and dams, such as El Lahun dam,

00:51:59.020 --> 00:52:02.740
which was erected during the reign of King Amenemhat III,

00:52:02.740 --> 00:52:04.660
who ruled in the 12th Dynasty,

00:52:04.660 --> 00:52:07.000
following the reign of Senusret III,

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:08.470
as he wanted to make good use

00:52:08.470 --> 00:52:11.530
of the floodwaters for the irrigation system,

00:52:11.530 --> 00:52:14.560
and to protect the state from destructive high levels

00:52:14.560 --> 00:52:16.180
of inundation water.

00:52:16.180 --> 00:52:17.980
Early November, before the water

00:52:17.980 --> 00:52:20.020
had entirely left the basins,

00:52:20.020 --> 00:52:23.590
was the time when preparations for planting season began.

00:52:23.590 --> 00:52:26.050
Before fields were prepared for planting,

00:52:26.050 --> 00:52:28.930
irrigation facilities were repaired or cleared,

00:52:28.930 --> 00:52:31.480
and property lines were reevaluated.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:33.640
And since ancient Egyptians were known

00:52:33.640 --> 00:52:36.880
to document every detail of their daily life,

00:52:36.880 --> 00:52:38.860
we have seen the process of growing

00:52:38.860 --> 00:52:41.980
and harvesting the grain depicted in great detail

00:52:41.980 --> 00:52:44.200
in various tombs' paintings.

00:52:44.200 --> 00:52:46.570
Various crops were planted widely,

00:52:46.570 --> 00:52:49.330
which made food types plentiful in Egypt,

00:52:49.330 --> 00:52:50.860
such as emmer wheat,

00:52:50.860 --> 00:52:52.960
which was used to make bread and beer,

00:52:52.960 --> 00:52:57.070
grapes for wine, palm dates, doom palms, figs,

00:52:57.070 --> 00:53:00.550
sycamore and papyrus, whose stems were used

00:53:00.550 --> 00:53:03.250
to make paper-like scrolls for writing,

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:05.290
and also was a great material

00:53:05.290 --> 00:53:08.770
to make sails, cords and even mats.

00:53:08.770 --> 00:53:11.050
Various tools were used by the farmers

00:53:11.050 --> 00:53:12.820
during the planting process,

00:53:12.820 --> 00:53:16.180
such as a very interesting one called shaduf.

00:53:16.180 --> 00:53:18.010
It's a hand operated device

00:53:18.010 --> 00:53:19.750
used to lift water from the river,

00:53:19.750 --> 00:53:22.450
which consists of a long pole with a bucket

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:24.130
hung on a rope from one end,

00:53:24.130 --> 00:53:26.560
and the other end has a weight attached to it.

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:28.180
It was either used to fill jugs

00:53:28.180 --> 00:53:29.920
with water to transport them,

00:53:29.920 --> 00:53:33.880
or even to run water in small canals along ditches.

00:53:33.880 --> 00:53:36.730
However, it's normal when people wonder

00:53:36.730 --> 00:53:39.730
how such a civilization in ancient times

00:53:39.730 --> 00:53:42.460
managed to erect huge buildings,

00:53:42.460 --> 00:53:46.180
and move colossal statues without having the technology

00:53:46.180 --> 00:53:48.610
we have in the current modern world.

00:53:48.610 --> 00:53:51.100
Some scenes from tombs of high officials

00:53:51.100 --> 00:53:53.410
have proof of how the whole process

00:53:53.410 --> 00:53:56.260
of moving huge statues was done.

00:53:56.260 --> 00:53:59.770
Djehuty-Nakht was a nomarch of the 12th Dynasty.

00:53:59.770 --> 00:54:03.580
He used to govern the 15th nome of Upper Egypt.

00:54:03.580 --> 00:54:06.400
He has a very interesting scene in his tomb

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:08.350
of the transportation of a roughly

00:54:08.350 --> 00:54:13.350
6.8 meter high monument of him by 172 people,

00:54:13.960 --> 00:54:17.110
using ropes in a slide in an endeavor aided

00:54:17.110 --> 00:54:20.110
by the dumping of water in front of the slide.

00:54:20.110 --> 00:54:21.940
Unfortunately, no evidence

00:54:21.940 --> 00:54:25.150
of this colossus has ever been discovered.

00:54:25.150 --> 00:54:29.230
Amenemhat III boasted of no major military triumphs,

00:54:29.230 --> 00:54:32.590
but constructed almost as many monuments as his father,

00:54:32.590 --> 00:54:36.430
and was responsible for the vast mortuary sanctuary

00:54:36.430 --> 00:54:39.520
at Hawara known as the Labyrinth.

00:54:39.520 --> 00:54:44.520
Amenemhat IV, 1815 to 1807 BCE, replaced him

00:54:45.460 --> 00:54:47.620
and maintained his policies.

00:54:47.620 --> 00:54:50.290
He completed his father's construction tasks

00:54:50.290 --> 00:54:52.330
and began many of his own.

00:54:52.330 --> 00:54:53.470
During his reign,

00:54:53.470 --> 00:54:55.750
military and commercial expeditions

00:54:55.750 --> 00:54:58.480
were undertaken on numerous occasions,

00:54:58.480 --> 00:55:01.750
and trade thrived with towns in the Levant,

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:04.537
particularly Byblos and elsewhere.

00:55:04.537 --> 00:55:08.200
The coregency policy, if it was implemented,

00:55:08.200 --> 00:55:11.050
had guaranteed a seamless transfer of power

00:55:11.050 --> 00:55:14.710
from ruler to ruler, but it failed in the case

00:55:14.710 --> 00:55:18.610
of Amenemhat IV who had no male successor

00:55:18.610 --> 00:55:20.710
to prepare for success.

00:55:20.710 --> 00:55:23.890
After his demise, the throne passed to his sister

00:55:23.890 --> 00:55:27.763
or probably wife Sobekneferu, 1807 to 1802 BCE,

00:55:30.730 --> 00:55:32.890
whose rule is little known.

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:36.400
Unless the Queen Nitiqret, Nitocris of the Sixth Dynasty

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:39.010
of the Old Kingdom is accepted as real,

00:55:39.010 --> 00:55:41.590
Sobekneferu was the first woman

00:55:41.590 --> 00:55:45.307
to govern Egypt since the Early Dynastic Period.

00:55:45.307 --> 00:55:47.290
The 12th Dynasty concluded

00:55:47.290 --> 00:55:49.360
when she perished without an heir,

00:55:49.360 --> 00:55:53.500
and the 13th started with the reign of Sobekhotep I,

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:56.950
1802 to 1800 BCE.

00:55:56.950 --> 00:55:58.630
The Middle Kingdom's 12th Period

00:55:58.630 --> 00:56:00.850
was the most powerful and wealthy.

00:56:00.850 --> 00:56:02.800
The 13th Dynasty would receive

00:56:02.800 --> 00:56:04.750
the riches and the policies,

00:56:04.750 --> 00:56:07.570
but would be unable to put them to good use.

00:56:07.570 --> 00:56:09.430
The 13th Dynasty appears

00:56:09.430 --> 00:56:11.020
to have maintained the policies

00:56:11.020 --> 00:56:12.940
of the 12th Dynasty monarchs

00:56:12.940 --> 00:56:15.010
and kept the nation united.

00:56:15.010 --> 00:56:17.170
But none of them had the personal power

00:56:17.170 --> 00:56:18.850
of the previous kings,

00:56:18.850 --> 00:56:21.340
according to incomplete documents.

00:56:21.340 --> 00:56:25.153
Lower Egypt started to develop its political groups.

00:56:28.472 --> 00:56:31.305
(dramatic music)

00:56:39.670 --> 00:56:42.100
This era starts when the Egyptian rulers

00:56:42.100 --> 00:56:45.190
of the 13th Dynasty relocate the capital

00:56:45.190 --> 00:56:48.700
from Itjtawy to Thebes, the former capital

00:56:48.700 --> 00:56:51.820
of the late 11th Dynasty in Upper Egypt,

00:56:51.820 --> 00:56:54.520
thereby weakening their grip on the North.

00:56:54.520 --> 00:56:59.520
Amenemhat I, 1991 to 1962 BCE,

00:56:59.530 --> 00:57:02.020
established the tiny settlement of Hutwaret

00:57:02.020 --> 00:57:05.410
in the far north at the start of the 12th Dynasty,

00:57:05.410 --> 00:57:07.660
which developed into a commercial hub

00:57:07.660 --> 00:57:10.660
with easy access to the sea and road paths

00:57:10.660 --> 00:57:13.780
to Sinai and the area of Palestine.

00:57:13.780 --> 00:57:15.670
During the 13th Dynasty,

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:17.410
effective trade and immigration

00:57:17.410 --> 00:57:20.620
brought an increase of Semitic people to Avaris,

00:57:20.620 --> 00:57:23.590
who ultimately grew wealthy and powerful enough

00:57:23.590 --> 00:57:26.800
to wield governmental power in the nation.

00:57:26.800 --> 00:57:28.330
These individuals were known

00:57:28.330 --> 00:57:32.350
to the Egyptians as Heqau-Khasut or Hyksos.

00:57:32.350 --> 00:57:35.410
The name of the Hyksos remains unclear.

00:57:35.410 --> 00:57:37.750
Many hypotheses have been proposed

00:57:37.750 --> 00:57:40.840
including the possibility that they were refugees

00:57:40.840 --> 00:57:43.510
escaping the Aryan invasion of Asia.

00:57:43.510 --> 00:57:46.840
The Nordic invasion hypothesis has been debunked,

00:57:46.840 --> 00:57:48.550
as has this assertion.

00:57:48.550 --> 00:57:51.010
The Egyptians refer to them as Asians,

00:57:51.010 --> 00:57:53.260
but this was a word used for anyone

00:57:53.260 --> 00:57:55.810
beyond the country's eastern boundary,

00:57:55.810 --> 00:57:58.270
from the Levant to Mesopotamia.

00:57:58.270 --> 00:58:00.280
During the late 13th Dynasty,

00:58:00.280 --> 00:58:02.350
the Egyptian monarch ceased supplying

00:58:02.350 --> 00:58:05.260
the border fortifications located in Nubia,

00:58:05.260 --> 00:58:08.200
and no additional soldiers were stationed there.

00:58:08.200 --> 00:58:11.110
The troops who were already stationed at the forts

00:58:11.110 --> 00:58:13.270
were never returned to Egypt,

00:58:13.270 --> 00:58:16.930
and the former garrisons became their permanent residence.

00:58:16.930 --> 00:58:19.900
These troops served as commerce intermediaries

00:58:19.900 --> 00:58:22.180
between the Egyptian city of Thebes

00:58:22.180 --> 00:58:23.830
and the kingdom of Kush.

00:58:23.830 --> 00:58:25.510
As the 13th Dynasty

00:58:25.510 --> 00:58:27.430
neglected matters to the south,

00:58:27.430 --> 00:58:29.470
just as they were doing to the north,

00:58:29.470 --> 00:58:32.920
the kingdom of Kush developed into a centralized power,

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:34.810
with its capital at Kerma.

00:58:34.810 --> 00:58:37.210
Some of the ancient Egyptian fortifications

00:58:37.210 --> 00:58:39.850
along the border were destroyed at some time,

00:58:39.850 --> 00:58:43.120
presumably during an assault, though this is unclear.

00:58:43.120 --> 00:58:45.730
What is evident is that as Egyptian government

00:58:45.730 --> 00:58:49.150
in Thebes disregarded Kush's influence in the south,

00:58:49.150 --> 00:58:50.890
Kush's power increased

00:58:50.890 --> 00:58:53.380
and the boundary became more flexible.

00:58:53.380 --> 00:58:56.290
The troops who had been left behind no longer saw it

00:58:56.290 --> 00:58:59.380
as their duty to protect against invasions,

00:58:59.380 --> 00:59:01.660
and had grown more acclimated to the role

00:59:01.660 --> 00:59:04.810
of traders than military men by this point.

00:59:04.810 --> 00:59:07.360
The monarchs documented for the latter portion

00:59:07.360 --> 00:59:11.800
of the 13th and 16th Dynasties are non-Egyptians,

00:59:11.800 --> 00:59:15.340
or at the very least, do not have Egyptian names

00:59:15.340 --> 00:59:17.680
and are considered Hyksos rulers.

00:59:17.680 --> 00:59:19.420
Their timeline is muddled,

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:22.690
and some names are only known from ceremonial items,

00:59:22.690 --> 00:59:25.930
while others are only known from pieces of kings lists,

00:59:25.930 --> 00:59:28.330
making dating problematic.

00:59:28.330 --> 00:59:32.680
The Hyksos achieved economic dominance of the eastern delta,

00:59:32.680 --> 00:59:35.500
and then pushed north, negotiating treaties

00:59:35.500 --> 00:59:38.680
and forging contracts with various nomarchs,

00:59:38.680 --> 00:59:41.980
governors of other districts in Lower Egypt,

00:59:41.980 --> 00:59:45.430
until they had conquered a sizable amount of territory

00:59:45.430 --> 00:59:47.920
and could exert political authority.

00:59:47.920 --> 00:59:49.853
Once established an Avaris,

00:59:49.853 --> 00:59:53.710
the Hyksos elevated Egyptians to positions of power,

00:59:53.710 --> 00:59:56.200
adopted Egyptian customs and attire,

00:59:56.200 --> 00:59:58.660
and absorbed Egyptian deity worship

00:59:58.660 --> 01:00:01.450
into their own beliefs and ceremonies.

01:00:01.450 --> 01:00:03.670
The Hyksos's monarchs established

01:00:03.670 --> 01:00:05.770
Egypt's 15th dynasty,

01:00:05.770 --> 01:00:07.390
but once they were evicted,

01:00:07.390 --> 01:00:09.130
the invading Thebens destroyed

01:00:09.130 --> 01:00:12.550
all traces of the Hyksos in Egypt.

01:00:12.550 --> 01:00:15.370
Only a few Hyksos rulers are known by name,

01:00:15.370 --> 01:00:17.650
thanks to the ruins of inscriptions

01:00:17.650 --> 01:00:21.310
and other texts discovered at Avaris and elsewhere,

01:00:21.310 --> 01:00:24.016
including the best known Apepi.

01:00:24.016 --> 01:00:26.800
Apepi was also known as Apophis,

01:00:26.800 --> 01:00:28.570
and had an Egyptian name related

01:00:28.570 --> 01:00:31.330
to the giant snake Apophis or Apep,

01:00:31.330 --> 01:00:33.910
the sun god Ra's nemesis.

01:00:33.910 --> 01:00:36.040
At the same time the Hyksos rose

01:00:36.040 --> 01:00:37.717
to prominence in northern Egypt,

01:00:37.717 --> 01:00:40.750
the Nubians rose to power in the south.

01:00:40.750 --> 01:00:44.380
The Middle Kingdom's 13th Dynasty, like Lower Egypt,

01:00:44.380 --> 01:00:47.620
had forgotten to pay attention to its southern frontier.

01:00:47.620 --> 01:00:50.440
Thebes remained Upper Egypt's capital,

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:53.620
but instead of dominating the entire nation,

01:00:53.620 --> 01:00:56.350
it was wedged between the Hyksos in the north

01:00:56.350 --> 01:00:58.420
and the Nubians in the south.

01:00:58.420 --> 01:01:01.090
According to Manetho, Apepi of the Hyksos

01:01:01.090 --> 01:01:06.090
wrote to the Theben king, Seqenenre Tao, 1580 BCE,

01:01:06.317 --> 01:01:08.590
"Do away with a hippopotamus pool

01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:10.120
to the east of the city,

01:01:10.120 --> 01:01:13.180
for it prevents me from sleeping day and night."

01:01:13.180 --> 01:01:16.330
The message was most likely about the Theben practice

01:01:16.330 --> 01:01:19.660
of hippopotamus hunting, which would've been insulting

01:01:19.660 --> 01:01:22.060
to the Hyksos who worshiped Seth

01:01:22.060 --> 01:01:25.360
and included the hippo in their religious observances.

01:01:25.360 --> 01:01:27.970
Tao, rather than complying with the request,

01:01:27.970 --> 01:01:30.610
saw it as a challenge to his autonomy

01:01:30.610 --> 01:01:32.530
and marched on Avaris.

01:01:32.530 --> 01:01:35.800
His mummy indicates that he was slain in battle,

01:01:35.800 --> 01:01:38.890
and this, together with the events that follow,

01:01:38.890 --> 01:01:43.087
reveals that the Thebens were vanquished in this fight.

01:01:43.087 --> 01:01:45.580
Tao's son Kamose took up the cause,

01:01:45.580 --> 01:01:48.010
lamenting bitterly in an inscription

01:01:48.010 --> 01:01:51.610
about having to pay the Asiatic's taxes,

01:01:51.610 --> 01:01:53.890
and dealing with outsiders to the north

01:01:53.890 --> 01:01:56.050
and south of him and his kingdom.

01:01:56.050 --> 01:01:59.020
He launched a huge attack on the Hyksos,

01:01:59.020 --> 01:02:01.690
destroying Avaris according to the narrative.

01:02:01.690 --> 01:02:05.290
Kamose reports that his attack was so fast and scary,

01:02:05.290 --> 01:02:07.840
that it rendered the Hyksos women barren,

01:02:07.840 --> 01:02:10.540
and that he destroyed the city to the ground

01:02:10.540 --> 01:02:12.190
following the carnage.

01:02:12.190 --> 01:02:14.680
This tale appears to be exaggerated,

01:02:14.680 --> 01:02:17.860
as the Hyksos retained control of Lower Egypt

01:02:17.860 --> 01:02:20.077
three years after Kamose's invasion,

01:02:20.077 --> 01:02:23.500
and Avaris remained Hyksos's stronghold.

01:02:23.500 --> 01:02:26.260
Kamose was succeeded by his brother Ahmose,

01:02:26.260 --> 01:02:28.240
who according to the inscriptions

01:02:28.240 --> 01:02:30.490
drove Hyksos out of Egypt

01:02:30.490 --> 01:02:33.430
and destroyed their metropolis of Avaris.

01:02:33.430 --> 01:02:35.980
These events are described in the tomb inscriptions

01:02:35.980 --> 01:02:38.650
of another man, Ahmose son of Ebana,

01:02:38.650 --> 01:02:41.200
a soldier who fought under King Ahmose,

01:02:41.200 --> 01:02:44.080
who describes the devastation of Avaris

01:02:44.080 --> 01:02:46.310
and the retreat of the remaining Hyksos

01:02:46.310 --> 01:02:49.210
to Sharuhen in the Palestine region.

01:02:49.210 --> 01:02:52.960
Ahmose then besieged this city for six years

01:02:52.960 --> 01:02:56.980
until the Hyksos fled again, this time to Syria,

01:02:56.980 --> 01:03:00.745
although what happened to them after that is unknown.

01:03:00.745 --> 01:03:04.600
Ahmose I not only established the 18th Dynasty,

01:03:04.600 --> 01:03:07.600
but also began the New Kingdom of Egypt,

01:03:07.600 --> 01:03:10.360
the age of the Egyptian empire.

01:03:10.360 --> 01:03:12.880
The Hyksos were responsible for the formation

01:03:12.880 --> 01:03:15.790
of a professional Egyptian army of conquest,

01:03:15.790 --> 01:03:19.030
since Ahmose I and those who followed him

01:03:19.030 --> 01:03:22.060
sought to ensure that no foreign nation

01:03:22.060 --> 01:03:25.360
ever gained such dominance in their land again.

01:03:25.360 --> 01:03:27.923
The triumph that would become the New Kingdom,

01:03:27.923 --> 01:03:32.140
a period of unprecedented prosperity and success in Egypt,

01:03:32.140 --> 01:03:35.677
is the legacy of the Second Intermediate Period.

01:03:35.677 --> 01:03:40.126
The 18th Dynasty of Egypt, established by Ahmose I,

01:03:40.126 --> 01:03:41.920
would build some of the most renowned

01:03:41.920 --> 01:03:46.030
and memorable monuments since the Old Kingdom's pyramids,

01:03:46.030 --> 01:03:49.153
and expand Egypt's borders into a kingdom.

01:03:54.097 --> 01:03:59.097
(vocalist singing in foreign language)

01:03:59.344 --> 01:04:02.594
(gentle upbeat music)

01:04:09.924 --> 01:04:13.390
Ahmose I realized that the Hyksos had been able

01:04:13.390 --> 01:04:16.210
to establish themselves so securely

01:04:16.210 --> 01:04:20.470
because previous Egyptian monarchs had permitted them to.

01:04:20.470 --> 01:04:24.070
As a result, he chose to establish protected areas

01:04:24.070 --> 01:04:26.110
around Egypt's boundaries,

01:04:26.110 --> 01:04:28.450
and fortifying neglected settlements

01:04:28.450 --> 01:04:31.570
in strategic locations to protect the nation.

01:04:31.570 --> 01:04:34.660
The battle of Ahmose I against the Hyksos

01:04:34.660 --> 01:04:36.790
brought him and his troops into touch

01:04:36.790 --> 01:04:39.880
with the areas of Palestine and Syria,

01:04:39.880 --> 01:04:42.190
where he continued his operations

01:04:42.190 --> 01:04:45.010
while also conducting military excursion

01:04:45.010 --> 01:04:48.370
south against the kingdom of Kush and Nubia.

01:04:48.370 --> 01:04:51.130
When he died, he had protected the nation

01:04:51.130 --> 01:04:53.320
and consolidated his authority,

01:04:53.320 --> 01:04:55.060
leaving a steady political

01:04:55.060 --> 01:04:57.880
and economic situation for his replacement,

01:04:57.880 --> 01:04:59.713
Amenhotep I, 1541 to 1520 BCE.

01:05:03.220 --> 01:05:05.740
Inscriptions show that Amenhotep I

01:05:05.740 --> 01:05:07.570
followed his father's policies

01:05:07.570 --> 01:05:10.990
and modeled himself after him as a warrior monarch,

01:05:10.990 --> 01:05:14.320
but he most likely only commanded battles into Nubia.

01:05:14.320 --> 01:05:15.670
There are no accounts of him

01:05:15.670 --> 01:05:18.910
conducting expeditions into Palestine or Syria,

01:05:18.910 --> 01:05:20.230
but he may have done so

01:05:20.230 --> 01:05:22.270
because those areas stayed secure

01:05:22.270 --> 01:05:25.480
during his and his successors' reigns.

01:05:25.480 --> 01:05:30.480
Thutmose I, 1520 to 1492 BCE, replaced him

01:05:31.270 --> 01:05:35.500
and immediately started wars to expand Egypt's reach.

01:05:35.500 --> 01:05:38.620
Thutmose I put down a revolt in Nubia

01:05:38.620 --> 01:05:41.320
that erupted soon after assuming the throne,

01:05:41.320 --> 01:05:44.560
personally murdering the Nubian monarch,

01:05:44.560 --> 01:05:48.220
and suspending his corpse from the prow of his ship

01:05:48.220 --> 01:05:50.650
as a caution to other rebels.

01:05:50.650 --> 01:05:54.700
He then extended Egypt's control over Nubia further south,

01:05:54.700 --> 01:05:58.420
before shifting his focus to Palestine and Syria.

01:05:58.420 --> 01:06:01.600
He expanded Thebe's famous temple of Karnak

01:06:01.600 --> 01:06:03.610
and built numerous other temples

01:06:03.610 --> 01:06:06.157
and structures throughout Egypt.

01:06:06.157 --> 01:06:11.157
Thutmose II, 1492 to 1479 BCE, succeeded him,

01:06:11.860 --> 01:06:13.690
but little is known about his rule

01:06:13.690 --> 01:06:15.580
because he was quickly eclipsed

01:06:15.580 --> 01:06:18.910
by his more potent half sister Hatshepsut.

01:06:18.910 --> 01:06:23.620
Hatshepsut, 1479 to 1458 BCE,

01:06:23.620 --> 01:06:25.660
was one of the most potent

01:06:25.660 --> 01:06:28.780
and effective New Kingdom rulers.

01:06:28.780 --> 01:06:31.660
Thutmose II had one child with her,

01:06:31.660 --> 01:06:35.260
and he had another with a minor woman, Thutmose III,

01:06:35.260 --> 01:06:39.823
whom he named as his successor, 1458 to 1425 BCE.

01:06:41.320 --> 01:06:43.480
Following Thutmose II's death,

01:06:43.480 --> 01:06:46.330
Hatshepsut was appointed regent of Egypt

01:06:46.330 --> 01:06:49.630
and officially co-ruled with Thutmose III.

01:06:49.630 --> 01:06:53.500
But she had been the force behind her husband's tenure

01:06:53.500 --> 01:06:57.520
and continued to do so as she saw fit after his death.

01:06:57.520 --> 01:06:58.960
Hatshepsut is in charge

01:06:58.960 --> 01:07:01.690
of numerous construction initiatives.

01:07:01.690 --> 01:07:05.410
She conducted the most successful expedition to Punt,

01:07:05.410 --> 01:07:07.870
added her works to the Temple at Karnak,

01:07:07.870 --> 01:07:10.990
and governed in harmony with Nubia to the south.

01:07:10.990 --> 01:07:14.320
Her construction undertakings were so beautiful

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:17.080
and numerous that subsequent pharaohs

01:07:17.080 --> 01:07:19.030
claimed ownership of them.

01:07:19.030 --> 01:07:22.000
They were able to do so because Hatshepsut's name

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:24.760
was taken from all of her structures,

01:07:24.760 --> 01:07:27.550
including her magnificent complex

01:07:27.550 --> 01:07:32.410
at Deir el-Bahari around 1458 BCE.

01:07:32.410 --> 01:07:33.850
Concerning the obelisks

01:07:33.850 --> 01:07:36.160
that were erected in the different temples,

01:07:36.160 --> 01:07:38.350
they were symbols of the sun god,

01:07:38.350 --> 01:07:41.800
and many of them can be found everywhere in the whole world,

01:07:41.800 --> 01:07:44.050
whether they were real Egyptian ones

01:07:44.050 --> 01:07:48.250
or modern ones imitating the ancient Egyptian obelisks.

01:07:48.250 --> 01:07:51.550
The process of carving one is not a paradox,

01:07:51.550 --> 01:07:53.950
as there is an unfinished one located

01:07:53.950 --> 01:07:56.260
in the quarries of granite in Aswan.

01:07:56.260 --> 01:07:58.720
Hatshepsut commissioned its construction,

01:07:58.720 --> 01:08:01.060
probably to accompany what became known

01:08:01.060 --> 01:08:05.080
as the Lateran Obelisk, which was originally at Karnak

01:08:05.080 --> 01:08:08.470
but was later brought to the Lateran Palace in Rome.

01:08:08.470 --> 01:08:10.960
Thutmose III inherited a wealthy

01:08:10.960 --> 01:08:14.740
and secure country in 1458 BCE,

01:08:14.740 --> 01:08:17.080
and wasted no time in improving it.

01:08:17.080 --> 01:08:20.740
Thutmose III establishes the Egyptian empire,

01:08:20.740 --> 01:08:23.020
which his descendants would sustain.

01:08:23.020 --> 01:08:25.600
He defeated the neighboring countries,

01:08:25.600 --> 01:08:27.460
and expanded Egypt's dominion

01:08:27.460 --> 01:08:30.280
further than it had ever been before,

01:08:30.280 --> 01:08:33.820
using the war chariot acquired from the Hyksos,

01:08:33.820 --> 01:08:37.000
bronze weaponry and better strategies.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:39.610
Over 20 years, he led at least

01:08:39.610 --> 01:08:43.300
17 separate military campaigns,

01:08:43.300 --> 01:08:46.120
subduing kingdoms from Libya to Syria,

01:08:46.120 --> 01:08:48.880
and extending Egypt's authority in the south

01:08:48.880 --> 01:08:51.850
from the region around Buhen down to Kurgus.

01:08:51.850 --> 01:08:55.990
When Hatshepsut died, Thutmose III ascended to power.

01:08:55.990 --> 01:08:58.540
Believing him to be weak and inexperienced,

01:08:58.540 --> 01:09:00.850
the king of the Syrian city of Kadesh

01:09:00.850 --> 01:09:04.540
instigated a revolt in the Egyptian province of Canaan,

01:09:04.540 --> 01:09:07.480
which swiftly gathered support from other places

01:09:07.480 --> 01:09:09.610
aiming to dethrone Egypt.

01:09:09.610 --> 01:09:12.400
This coalition met in the city of Megiddo.

01:09:12.400 --> 01:09:15.670
Thutmose III marched his army from Thebes

01:09:15.670 --> 01:09:17.800
to Megiddo in northern Canaan,

01:09:17.800 --> 01:09:19.870
prudently choosing a narrow pass

01:09:19.870 --> 01:09:21.190
from the town of Aruna,

01:09:21.190 --> 01:09:24.430
instead of the wider and easier routes to the city,

01:09:24.430 --> 01:09:27.670
and surprised his enemies by entering the Kena Valley

01:09:27.670 --> 01:09:30.340
behind their defensive positions,

01:09:30.340 --> 01:09:32.650
and driving them from the field.

01:09:32.650 --> 01:09:36.640
Thutmose III had to lay siege to the city to seize it.

01:09:36.640 --> 01:09:39.400
Tjaneni, who was Thutmose III's commander

01:09:39.400 --> 01:09:42.460
and military scribe naturally accompanied

01:09:42.460 --> 01:09:45.310
his monarch in war to put down the rebellion,

01:09:45.310 --> 01:09:47.650
and wrote a record describing the fight.

01:09:47.650 --> 01:09:51.130
Thutmose III was so taken by Tjaneni's tale

01:09:51.130 --> 01:09:52.810
that he had sections of it written

01:09:52.810 --> 01:09:56.110
on the walls of the Great Temple of Amun at Karnak,

01:09:56.110 --> 01:09:58.960
and to a lesser extent elsewhere.

01:09:58.960 --> 01:10:00.790
Tjaneni begins by describing

01:10:00.790 --> 01:10:03.610
why the writing on the temple's walls exist.

01:10:03.610 --> 01:10:07.480
He then goes on to explain the campaign and its motivations.

01:10:07.480 --> 01:10:11.170
The wretched adversary referenced on several occasions

01:10:11.170 --> 01:10:14.140
is the King of Kadesh, who started the revolt

01:10:14.140 --> 01:10:16.630
and gathered the armies against Egypt.

01:10:16.630 --> 01:10:19.120
But it is also used to refer to everyone

01:10:19.120 --> 01:10:21.850
who joined the rebellion at times.

01:10:21.850 --> 01:10:23.710
Following the Battle of Megiddo,

01:10:23.710 --> 01:10:27.580
Thutmose III would subdue and punish those who took part,

01:10:27.580 --> 01:10:31.630
capturing not just Kadesh but also all of Syria

01:10:31.630 --> 01:10:35.050
and the Mitanni territories in Mesopotamia.

01:10:35.050 --> 01:10:40.050
He was succeeded by his Amenhotep II, 1425 to 1400 BCE,

01:10:41.980 --> 01:10:43.330
who inherited and built

01:10:43.330 --> 01:10:45.990
on his father's powerful and safe kingdom.

01:10:45.990 --> 01:10:48.160
He was not a warrior king,

01:10:48.160 --> 01:10:50.950
but he did order many construction projects

01:10:50.950 --> 01:10:53.560
and signed peace treaties and commerce deals

01:10:53.560 --> 01:10:56.080
with other countries, such as Mitanni.

01:10:56.080 --> 01:11:00.610
Thutmose IV, 1400 to 1390 BCE,

01:11:00.610 --> 01:11:04.090
his replacement, carried on his programs.

01:11:04.090 --> 01:11:07.090
Based on readings of renowned Dream Stele,

01:11:07.090 --> 01:11:10.030
which recounts the tale of how he came to the kingdom,

01:11:10.030 --> 01:11:13.060
Thutmose IV is regarded as a usurper,

01:11:13.060 --> 01:11:16.330
although he's the legal son of Amenhotep II.

01:11:16.330 --> 01:11:17.680
He's best known as the king

01:11:17.680 --> 01:11:20.710
who rebuilt Giza's Great Pyramid.

01:11:20.710 --> 01:11:23.230
He is followed by a Amenhotep III,

01:11:23.230 --> 01:11:27.910
1386 to 1353 BCE, who is regarded

01:11:27.910 --> 01:11:32.170
as one of Egypt's most effective and powerful rulers.

01:11:32.170 --> 01:11:35.140
Amenhotep III ruled Egypt at a time

01:11:35.140 --> 01:11:39.610
when it was at its artistic, political and fiscal apex.

01:11:39.610 --> 01:11:44.200
His reign was one of the most opulent in Egyptian history,

01:11:44.200 --> 01:11:46.210
and he frequently used his riches

01:11:46.210 --> 01:11:49.810
to persuade other nations to do what he desired.

01:11:49.810 --> 01:11:53.320
He kept the nation stable, enlarged its boundaries,

01:11:53.320 --> 01:11:55.330
and devoted himself to the arts

01:11:55.330 --> 01:11:57.370
and construction initiatives.

01:11:57.370 --> 01:12:00.310
Many of Egypt's most impressive structures

01:12:00.310 --> 01:12:02.050
date from his rule.

01:12:02.050 --> 01:12:04.690
During his reign, however, the priests of Amun

01:12:04.690 --> 01:12:07.690
started to acquire increasing fortune.

01:12:07.690 --> 01:12:10.720
They possessed more property than the monarch,

01:12:10.720 --> 01:12:13.420
and used it to enrich themselves further.

01:12:13.420 --> 01:12:15.850
Amenhotep III attempted to contain

01:12:15.850 --> 01:12:17.440
their increasing influence

01:12:17.440 --> 01:12:19.690
by allying the himself with Aton,

01:12:19.690 --> 01:12:22.810
a minor deity symbolized by a sun disc.

01:12:22.810 --> 01:12:25.120
He appears to have believed that the authority

01:12:25.120 --> 01:12:27.880
of the pharaoh behind the worship of Aton

01:12:27.880 --> 01:12:29.170
would elevate the status

01:12:29.170 --> 01:12:31.960
of those priests over those of Amun.

01:12:31.960 --> 01:12:36.100
His scheme failed, but it did elevate the deity Aton,

01:12:36.100 --> 01:12:37.810
who would play an important role

01:12:37.810 --> 01:12:41.260
in the rule of Amenhotep's son and successor.

01:12:41.260 --> 01:12:44.650
Amenhotep IV, also known as Akhenaten,

01:12:44.650 --> 01:12:46.960
was an Egyptian pharaoh renowned

01:12:46.960 --> 01:12:49.060
for establishing monotheism

01:12:49.060 --> 01:12:51.640
and banishing the ancient gods.

01:12:51.640 --> 01:12:54.760
His rule became known as the Amarna Period,

01:12:54.760 --> 01:12:57.190
because the Egyptian capital was relocated

01:12:57.190 --> 01:13:00.160
from Thebes to modern day Amarna.

01:13:00.160 --> 01:13:03.130
He ascended to the kingdom as Amenhotep IV,

01:13:03.130 --> 01:13:05.110
but changed his name to Akhenaten

01:13:05.110 --> 01:13:07.300
in the fourth or fifth year of his rule,

01:13:07.300 --> 01:13:09.310
dissolved the old religion,

01:13:09.310 --> 01:13:11.590
particularly the worship of Amun,

01:13:11.590 --> 01:13:14.350
and raised the deity Aton to the position

01:13:14.350 --> 01:13:16.390
of the one true god.

01:13:16.390 --> 01:13:18.880
Only the cult of Aton was recognized

01:13:18.880 --> 01:13:21.760
as a valid religious organization.

01:13:21.760 --> 01:13:24.100
All other sanctuaries were shuttered

01:13:24.100 --> 01:13:26.440
and their veneration was prohibited.

01:13:26.440 --> 01:13:28.050
He built a shrine to attend Aton

01:13:28.050 --> 01:13:30.250
at Karnak's great temple of Amun,

01:13:30.250 --> 01:13:32.140
which he also shuttered.

01:13:32.140 --> 01:13:35.110
His wife was the famous Nefertiti,

01:13:35.110 --> 01:13:37.540
best known for the magnificent bust

01:13:37.540 --> 01:13:40.240
created by the sculptor Thutmose.

01:13:40.240 --> 01:13:44.470
Upon Akhenaten's death, he was succeeded by his young son

01:13:44.470 --> 01:13:49.470
Tutankhaten, 1336 to 1327 BCE,

01:13:49.600 --> 01:13:52.870
who quickly changed his name to Tutankhamun,

01:13:52.870 --> 01:13:56.530
who took to the throne at just nine years old.

01:13:56.530 --> 01:13:59.620
The young leader relocated the capital to Memphis,

01:13:59.620 --> 01:14:02.230
restored Thebes as a religious center,

01:14:02.230 --> 01:14:04.810
which also held political significance,

01:14:04.810 --> 01:14:08.920
reopened the temples and restored Egypt's ancient religion.

01:14:08.920 --> 01:14:11.980
Although he instituted significant changes

01:14:11.980 --> 01:14:13.750
that helped secure the nation,

01:14:13.750 --> 01:14:16.630
he's best known for his magnificent tomb,

01:14:16.630 --> 01:14:20.080
which Howard Carter found in 1922.

01:14:20.080 --> 01:14:22.540
Tutankhamun was married to Ankhesenamun,

01:14:22.540 --> 01:14:27.540
his half-sister, until his demise at the age of about 18.

01:14:27.850 --> 01:14:31.150
Ankhesenamun may then have married the vizier Ay,

01:14:31.150 --> 01:14:35.410
possibly 1324 to 1320 BCE,

01:14:35.410 --> 01:14:38.380
who some experts believe replaced Tutankhamun,

01:14:38.380 --> 01:14:41.110
or she may have attempted to reign on her own.

01:14:41.110 --> 01:14:43.750
Whatever part Ay played in the succession,

01:14:43.750 --> 01:14:47.260
Ankhesenamun vanished soon after Tutankhamun's death,

01:14:47.260 --> 01:14:50.170
and the general Horemheb took control,

01:14:50.170 --> 01:14:53.830
devoting to return Egypt to its former grandeur.

01:14:53.830 --> 01:14:57.663
Horemheb, 1320 to 1295 BCE,

01:14:57.663 --> 01:14:59.440
went to great measures

01:14:59.440 --> 01:15:03.160
to erase the Amarna Period rulers from Egyptian history

01:15:03.160 --> 01:15:06.220
by burning all of the Akhenaten's statues and writings,

01:15:06.220 --> 01:15:08.290
including completely demolishing

01:15:08.290 --> 01:15:10.540
his sanctuary at Karnak.

01:15:10.540 --> 01:15:14.860
Horemheb defended traditional Egyptian religion and customs.

01:15:14.860 --> 01:15:16.810
Relationships with other countries

01:15:16.810 --> 01:15:18.550
and Egypt's infrastructure

01:15:18.550 --> 01:15:21.430
were ignored Akhenaten's rule.

01:15:21.430 --> 01:15:24.490
Horemheb returned Egypt to its previous glory,

01:15:24.490 --> 01:15:26.410
though he was unable to bring it back

01:15:26.410 --> 01:15:28.810
to the heights of Amenhotep III.

01:15:28.810 --> 01:15:30.790
He perished without an heir,

01:15:30.790 --> 01:15:35.680
and his vizier Paramesse seized the kingdom as Ramesses I,

01:15:35.680 --> 01:15:38.470
establishing the 19th Dynasty.

01:15:38.470 --> 01:15:40.930
Ramesses I was an elderly man

01:15:40.930 --> 01:15:42.670
when he ascended to the kingdom,

01:15:42.670 --> 01:15:47.440
and he swiftly named his son Seti I as his successor.

01:15:47.440 --> 01:15:50.290
Ramesses I resumed Horemheb's task

01:15:50.290 --> 01:15:53.470
of rebuilding Egypt's sanctuaries and shrines,

01:15:53.470 --> 01:15:57.130
as well as adding to the vast temple of Amun at Karnak.

01:15:57.130 --> 01:15:59.350
He gave Seti I the authority

01:15:59.350 --> 01:16:02.800
to lead military missions to reclaim areas lost

01:16:02.800 --> 01:16:04.510
during Akhenaten's rule.

01:16:04.510 --> 01:16:07.750
When he passed, Seti I ascended to the throne

01:16:07.750 --> 01:16:10.900
and continued Egypt's reform and revival,

01:16:10.900 --> 01:16:14.050
adding his own touches to the big project at Karmak,

01:16:14.050 --> 01:16:16.780
and grooming his successor for dominance.

01:16:16.780 --> 01:16:21.523
His son, Ramesses II, 1279 to 1213 BCE.

01:16:22.930 --> 01:16:27.040
He is the most well-known pharaoh of Egypt today.

01:16:27.040 --> 01:16:31.840
Ramesses I governed Egypt for 67 years,

01:16:31.840 --> 01:16:34.300
and the magnificent temples and monuments

01:16:34.300 --> 01:16:36.970
he constructed in celebration of his conquests

01:16:36.970 --> 01:16:40.150
and accomplishments still stand as a testament

01:16:40.150 --> 01:16:41.740
to the wealth of his reign.

01:16:41.740 --> 01:16:44.650
There is hardly any ancient Egyptian site

01:16:44.650 --> 01:16:46.640
that does not mention Ramesses I

01:16:47.510 --> 01:16:49.300
and the story of his triumph

01:16:49.300 --> 01:16:54.300
in the Battle of Kadesh in 1274 BC is legendary.

01:16:54.370 --> 01:16:57.400
However, one of his greatest acts as pharaoh

01:16:57.400 --> 01:17:00.400
was not one of battle but one of peace,

01:17:00.400 --> 01:17:05.020
the forging the first peace treaty in history.

01:17:05.020 --> 01:17:07.660
Anatolia's Hittites had been gaining prominence

01:17:07.660 --> 01:17:10.060
since the second millennium BC,

01:17:10.060 --> 01:17:13.840
and by 1530 BC, they had surpassed Babylonia

01:17:13.840 --> 01:17:17.830
as a notable nation and they were putting Egypt to the test.

01:17:17.830 --> 01:17:19.510
Letters of intent had been addressed

01:17:19.510 --> 01:17:22.270
to the 18th Dynasty's King Akhenaten,

01:17:22.270 --> 01:17:23.920
but he had never responded

01:17:23.920 --> 01:17:27.760
or taken note of Hittite activities along his boundaries.

01:17:27.760 --> 01:17:31.930
Horemheb had waged unsuccessfully against the Hittites,

01:17:31.930 --> 01:17:33.700
who had grown even more strong

01:17:33.700 --> 01:17:37.060
by the time of Tutankhamun, Akhenaten's successor,

01:17:37.060 --> 01:17:39.880
and were daring enough to garrison districts

01:17:39.880 --> 01:17:42.760
on or near Egypt's borders.

01:17:42.760 --> 01:17:47.020
When Horemheb became Pharaoh in 1320 BCE,

01:17:47.020 --> 01:17:50.530
he initiated a more forceful campaign against the Hittites

01:17:50.530 --> 01:17:52.960
and secured Egypt's frontiers,

01:17:52.960 --> 01:17:55.300
although the problem of the Hittite invasions

01:17:55.300 --> 01:17:57.220
was never fully overcome.

01:17:57.220 --> 01:18:01.030
Seti I had gained Palestine and Kadesh for Egypt,

01:18:01.030 --> 01:18:04.030
but happy with the victory had made no plans

01:18:04.030 --> 01:18:05.740
for the city's defense.

01:18:05.740 --> 01:18:09.790
Now Ramesses II of the 19th Dynasty had to cope

01:18:09.790 --> 01:18:12.310
with the problem of the Hittite invasion,

01:18:12.310 --> 01:18:17.260
and gathered his forces at Pi-Ramesses in 1274 BC

01:18:17.260 --> 01:18:20.980
to remove the Hittites from Kadesh and weaken their army.

01:18:20.980 --> 01:18:24.400
Riding in his chariot at the head of four divisions,

01:18:24.400 --> 01:18:28.330
20,000 soldiers, Ramesses II marched

01:18:28.330 --> 01:18:30.820
his first division so quickly

01:18:30.820 --> 01:18:33.670
that he soon out distanced the other three.

01:18:33.670 --> 01:18:36.430
Near Kadesh, two Bedouins were apprehended

01:18:36.430 --> 01:18:37.780
and asked about the whereabouts

01:18:37.780 --> 01:18:40.150
of Muwatalli II and his army,

01:18:40.150 --> 01:18:43.750
to which they replied that the army was nowhere near Kadesh

01:18:43.750 --> 01:18:48.220
and that Muwatalli II feared Egypt and the young king.

01:18:48.220 --> 01:18:51.310
The Bedouins, however, were Hittite spies,

01:18:51.310 --> 01:18:54.880
and Muwatalli II had already fortified Kadesh

01:18:54.880 --> 01:18:58.240
with his chariots, 3,500 of them,

01:18:58.240 --> 01:19:01.450
and troops, 37,000 men

01:19:01.450 --> 01:19:03.850
waiting just over the next hill.

01:19:03.850 --> 01:19:06.100
According to some combat accounts,

01:19:06.100 --> 01:19:09.190
Ramesses II caught several more spies,

01:19:09.190 --> 01:19:12.400
who told the awful reality about his condition,

01:19:12.400 --> 01:19:14.560
but the information arrived too late.

01:19:14.560 --> 01:19:16.930
Ramesses II had separated himself

01:19:16.930 --> 01:19:20.470
from the rest of his army in his haste to seize Kadesh

01:19:20.470 --> 01:19:22.780
and vanquish the Hittite ruler.

01:19:22.780 --> 01:19:26.920
Just as the Hittite chariots slammed into his camp,

01:19:26.920 --> 01:19:30.847
he dispatched messages to the other three divisions.

01:19:30.847 --> 01:19:32.800
The Ptah division arrived in time

01:19:32.800 --> 01:19:35.110
to prevent an Egyptian army defeat,

01:19:35.110 --> 01:19:37.630
and Ramesses II personally led

01:19:37.630 --> 01:19:41.500
the remaining Amun division into action many times,

01:19:41.500 --> 01:19:45.070
pushing the Hittite soldiers back onto Orontes River,

01:19:45.070 --> 01:19:46.690
where many perished.

01:19:46.690 --> 01:19:50.710
Muwatalli II just only marched from Kadesh's walls

01:19:50.710 --> 01:19:53.170
to trap Ramesses II's forces

01:19:53.170 --> 01:19:56.350
between his army by the river and his advance,

01:19:56.350 --> 01:20:00.670
but for unexplained reasons, he chose to stay in the city

01:20:00.670 --> 01:20:03.700
and never committed his reserve men to fight.

01:20:03.700 --> 01:20:07.630
Ramesses II declared a great triumph at Kadesh

01:20:07.630 --> 01:20:09.640
and had a scribe record his narrative

01:20:09.640 --> 01:20:11.490
of the wonderful fight.

01:20:11.490 --> 01:20:14.740
Muwatalli II's version differed significantly,

01:20:14.740 --> 01:20:18.070
most notably in claiming Kadesh as a Hittite victory.

01:20:18.070 --> 01:20:20.740
While Ramesses II did not capture the city,

01:20:20.740 --> 01:20:23.620
he did break the Hittite army on the field,

01:20:23.620 --> 01:20:27.180
and while Muwatalli II kept possession of Kadesh,

01:20:27.180 --> 01:20:30.670
he did not destroy the Egyptians as he had intended.

01:20:30.670 --> 01:20:34.150
Merneptah was Ramesses II's 12th son

01:20:34.150 --> 01:20:36.460
and not his designated successor.

01:20:36.460 --> 01:20:37.990
He only became pharaoh

01:20:37.990 --> 01:20:40.360
because all of his siblings had perished

01:20:40.360 --> 01:20:42.760
during their father's lengthy rule.

01:20:42.760 --> 01:20:45.340
Merneptah soon adopted his father's image

01:20:45.340 --> 01:20:49.210
of a warrior monarch, defeating the Libyans in combat

01:20:49.210 --> 01:20:51.880
and repelling an attack on the sea peoples.

01:20:51.880 --> 01:20:53.590
His description of his exploits

01:20:53.590 --> 01:20:56.140
include the well-known Merneptah Stele,

01:20:56.140 --> 01:20:58.330
which contains the first reference

01:20:58.330 --> 01:21:00.700
to the Israelites as a tribe.

01:21:00.700 --> 01:21:03.190
Going forth to the 20th dynasty,

01:21:03.190 --> 01:21:07.750
Ramesses III was the New Kingdom's last powerful king.

01:21:07.750 --> 01:21:10.810
After Horemheb restored the ancient faith,

01:21:10.810 --> 01:21:13.810
the priests of Amun's authority grew steadily,

01:21:13.810 --> 01:21:16.960
drawing income and influence away from the monarchy.

01:21:16.960 --> 01:21:19.990
Throughout the Ramessed era of the 20th Dynasty,

01:21:19.990 --> 01:21:21.970
the condition deteriorated.

01:21:21.970 --> 01:21:24.550
The concept of having a war was existing

01:21:24.550 --> 01:21:28.030
as the threat of the people was remarkably increasing,

01:21:28.030 --> 01:21:31.960
which forced Ramesses III to declare war over them.

01:21:31.960 --> 01:21:34.750
The nationality of the sea peoples is unknown

01:21:34.750 --> 01:21:36.160
because the only records

01:21:36.160 --> 01:21:38.650
of their activities are from Egyptian sources

01:21:38.650 --> 01:21:41.350
that only describe them in the terms of battle,

01:21:41.350 --> 01:21:45.077
such as the record from the Tanis Stele which reads in part,

01:21:45.077 --> 01:21:47.860
"They came from the sea in their warships

01:21:47.860 --> 01:21:50.050
and none could stand against them."

01:21:50.050 --> 01:21:52.540
This is characteristic of Egyptian allusions

01:21:52.540 --> 01:21:54.730
to these enigmatic invaders.

01:21:54.730 --> 01:21:58.540
Ramesses II, his son and successor Merneptah,

01:21:58.540 --> 01:22:02.170
and Ramesses III are the three great pharaohs

01:22:02.170 --> 01:22:04.870
who chronicle their struggles and triumphs

01:22:04.870 --> 01:22:06.910
against the sea peoples.

01:22:06.910 --> 01:22:10.060
All claimed huge victories over their opponents,

01:22:10.060 --> 01:22:12.700
and their inscriptions include the most extensive

01:22:12.700 --> 01:22:15.640
documentation of the sea peoples.

01:22:15.640 --> 01:22:18.250
During the time of Pharaoh Ramesses III,

01:22:18.250 --> 01:22:19.570
the sea peoples invaded

01:22:19.570 --> 01:22:23.317
and destroyed the Egyptian commerce hub at Kadesh,

01:22:23.317 --> 01:22:26.080
and then attempted to invade Egypt again.

01:22:26.080 --> 01:22:27.550
They began their operations

01:22:27.550 --> 01:22:29.740
with swift attacks along the coast,

01:22:29.740 --> 01:22:31.200
before pushing toward the delta.

01:22:31.200 --> 01:22:35.320
In 1180 BC, Ramesses III subdued them,

01:22:35.320 --> 01:22:37.300
but they returned in force.

01:22:37.300 --> 01:22:39.220
Ramesses III would've been aware

01:22:39.220 --> 01:22:41.440
of his predecessors fights with these people

01:22:41.440 --> 01:22:43.150
and how violent they were.

01:22:43.150 --> 01:22:45.520
He decided against a field engagement,

01:22:45.520 --> 01:22:48.880
and instead employed guerrilla tactics as a plan.

01:22:48.880 --> 01:22:51.010
He set up ambushes around the coast

01:22:51.010 --> 01:22:52.810
and along the Nile Delta,

01:22:52.810 --> 01:22:55.420
and his archers were especially efficient,

01:22:55.420 --> 01:22:57.520
putting them camouflaged along the beach

01:22:57.520 --> 01:23:00.940
to shower down arrows on the ships at his signal.

01:23:00.940 --> 01:23:03.640
The ships were set on fire with burning arrows

01:23:03.640 --> 01:23:06.130
once the crew was dead or drowning.

01:23:06.130 --> 01:23:08.800
After crushing the naval invasion,

01:23:08.800 --> 01:23:11.710
Ramesses III turned his focus to what remained

01:23:11.710 --> 01:23:13.690
of the invading troops on land.

01:23:13.690 --> 01:23:16.541
He used the same tactics as previously,

01:23:16.541 --> 01:23:20.830
and in 1178 BC, the sea peoples were defeated

01:23:20.830 --> 01:23:22.660
off the coast of Xois.

01:23:22.660 --> 01:23:27.070
Egyptian annals once again depict a spectacular victory

01:23:27.070 --> 01:23:29.710
in which many sea peoples were slaughtered,

01:23:29.710 --> 01:23:31.570
and others were captured and coerced

01:23:31.570 --> 01:23:35.560
into the Egyptian army and fleet, or sold as slaves.

01:23:35.560 --> 01:23:39.010
Although Ramesses III spared Egypt from invasion,

01:23:39.010 --> 01:23:40.570
the battle was so costly

01:23:40.570 --> 01:23:43.000
that the royal treasury was depleted,

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:46.960
and the tomb builders at Deir el-Medina could not be paid.

01:23:46.960 --> 01:23:50.530
This resulted in the first documented labor strike

01:23:50.530 --> 01:23:53.770
in history in which workers walked off the job

01:23:53.770 --> 01:23:57.640
and refused to return until they were properly reimbursed.

01:23:57.640 --> 01:23:59.680
And then the momentum

01:23:59.680 --> 01:24:02.800
of the Egyptian empire started to fade.

01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:06.730
Ramesses III retained a powerful central authority,

01:24:06.730 --> 01:24:10.330
secured the borders and kept Egypt prosperous,

01:24:10.330 --> 01:24:13.060
but the kingdom was crumbling around him.

01:24:13.060 --> 01:24:15.100
The office of the pharaoh of Egypt

01:24:15.100 --> 01:24:17.380
no longer held the same level of reverence

01:24:17.380 --> 01:24:19.750
it once did because the priests of Amun

01:24:19.750 --> 01:24:23.200
served as an intermediary between the gods.

01:24:23.200 --> 01:24:26.650
Ramesses III was injured in an assassination attempt

01:24:26.650 --> 01:24:29.410
staged by one of his lesser spouses

01:24:29.410 --> 01:24:32.260
and perished as a result of his injuries.

01:24:32.260 --> 01:24:37.260
Ramesses IV, 1155 to 1149 BCE, ascended to the throne

01:24:38.710 --> 01:24:41.650
only after his elder siblings perished.

01:24:41.650 --> 01:24:45.010
He attempted to imitate the great pharaohs of the past

01:24:45.010 --> 01:24:48.340
and did complete several construction projects,

01:24:48.340 --> 01:24:52.090
while battling to keep the empire's declining territory.

01:24:52.090 --> 01:24:54.790
But he perished after a brief rule.

01:24:54.790 --> 01:24:57.880
He was succeeded by his son, Ramesses V,

01:24:57.880 --> 01:25:01.060
who fought to retain control against Amun's priests

01:25:01.060 --> 01:25:02.650
and keep the kingdom together.

01:25:02.650 --> 01:25:05.080
His successor, Ramesses VI,

01:25:05.080 --> 01:25:07.690
carried on the fight with little success.

01:25:07.690 --> 01:25:09.820
Ramesses VII replaced him,

01:25:09.820 --> 01:25:13.691
followed by Ramesses VIII, about whom little is known.

01:25:13.691 --> 01:25:18.310
Ramesses IX, Ramesses X, and Ramesses XI.

01:25:18.310 --> 01:25:20.230
All of these pharaohs fought

01:25:20.230 --> 01:25:21.730
to keep the kingdom together

01:25:21.730 --> 01:25:24.100
in the face of outside incursions

01:25:24.100 --> 01:25:27.280
and internal conflicts with Amun's priests.

01:25:27.280 --> 01:25:30.490
An incident related to these struggles, though obscure,

01:25:30.490 --> 01:25:34.300
involves a man called Amenhotep, High Priest of Amun,

01:25:34.300 --> 01:25:36.850
who was deposed by the vizier Pinehesy

01:25:36.850 --> 01:25:39.430
and forced to escape south to Nubia.

01:25:39.430 --> 01:25:42.520
What we are sure about is that the priests of Amun

01:25:42.520 --> 01:25:46.720
retained huge power and reached the throne of Egypt

01:25:46.720 --> 01:25:48.710
and ruled the country.

01:25:48.710 --> 01:25:51.543
(dramatic music)

01:26:17.350 --> 01:26:21.820
Smendes, 1077 to 1051 BCE,

01:26:21.820 --> 01:26:24.790
a ruler of Lower Egypt who governed from Tanis,

01:26:24.790 --> 01:26:26.920
interred Ramesses XI.

01:26:26.920 --> 01:26:28.900
Following the Egyptian custom,

01:26:28.900 --> 01:26:31.267
a monarch was buried by his successor,

01:26:31.267 --> 01:26:34.330
and Smendes asserted his legal right to govern

01:26:34.330 --> 01:26:38.560
by relocating the capital from Pi-Ramesses to Tanis.

01:26:38.560 --> 01:26:41.470
However, by this time, the priests of Thebes

01:26:41.470 --> 01:26:43.090
had grown strong enough to assert

01:26:43.090 --> 01:26:46.270
their authority to rule, and the nation was divided

01:26:46.270 --> 01:26:49.300
between Tanis's control over Lower Egypt

01:26:49.300 --> 01:26:52.270
and Thebes's rule over Upper Egypt.

01:26:52.270 --> 01:26:54.130
Contrary to popular belief,

01:26:54.130 --> 01:26:58.450
this split did not end in civil conflict or internal strife.

01:26:58.450 --> 01:27:00.640
Smendes was strong enough to be noticed,

01:27:00.640 --> 01:27:04.120
but he only controlled Lower Egypt and not much of it.

01:27:04.120 --> 01:27:05.740
He governed around the same period

01:27:05.740 --> 01:27:07.720
of Thebes high priest Herihor,

01:27:07.720 --> 01:27:12.093
who reigned from around 1080 to 1074 BCE.

01:27:12.093 --> 01:27:14.380
Herihor was a general of the troops,

01:27:14.380 --> 01:27:16.870
as were all Amun's high priests.

01:27:16.870 --> 01:27:20.080
But he had little impact outside of Thebes.

01:27:20.080 --> 01:27:22.990
This would be the dominant model for the majority

01:27:22.990 --> 01:27:25.330
of the Third Intermediate era.

01:27:25.330 --> 01:27:27.580
Individual nomarchs were strengthened

01:27:27.580 --> 01:27:30.430
at the cost of either part of the central government,

01:27:30.430 --> 01:27:32.740
as in the First Intermediate Period,

01:27:32.740 --> 01:27:36.010
and both Tanis and Thebes failed to exercise

01:27:36.010 --> 01:27:39.760
any major influence over the nation as a whole.

01:27:39.760 --> 01:27:42.760
The 22nd Dynasty, which governed publicly

01:27:42.760 --> 01:27:46.450
under Libyan titles, was also Libyan.

01:27:46.450 --> 01:27:51.010
Shoshenq I, 943 to 922 BCE,

01:27:51.010 --> 01:27:53.710
established it after unifying Egypt

01:27:53.710 --> 01:27:55.930
and embarking on war operations

01:27:55.930 --> 01:27:58.900
reminiscent of Egypt's empire days.

01:27:58.900 --> 01:28:02.110
Shoshenq I reformed Tanis's administration

01:28:02.110 --> 01:28:03.640
and Thebes's clergy.

01:28:03.640 --> 01:28:06.640
The clergy would no longer be a hereditary post,

01:28:06.640 --> 01:28:09.610
but rather one of nomination by the monarch,

01:28:09.610 --> 01:28:12.610
as would be the choice of god's wife of Amun.

01:28:12.610 --> 01:28:16.780
His military operations revitalized Egypt's economy,

01:28:16.780 --> 01:28:19.080
and the nation started to approach the Egypt

01:28:19.080 --> 01:28:21.790
of the New Kingdom during his reign.

01:28:21.790 --> 01:28:26.380
Osorkon II descended to the throne in 872 BCE

01:28:26.380 --> 01:28:28.000
and kept the nation together.

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:29.380
But after his rule,

01:28:29.380 --> 01:28:31.900
Egypt split into distinct kingdoms,

01:28:31.900 --> 01:28:34.420
governing from Herakleopolis, Tanis,

01:28:34.420 --> 01:28:38.530
Sais, Memphis, and Hermopolis in Lower Egypt,

01:28:38.530 --> 01:28:40.780
and Thebes in Upper Egypt.

01:28:40.780 --> 01:28:43.606
To the south, the Kushite ruler Kashta,

01:28:43.606 --> 01:28:48.606
750 BCE, saw Egypt's vulnerability and moved to exploit it.

01:28:48.670 --> 01:28:51.280
Kashta adored Egyptian culture

01:28:51.280 --> 01:28:54.700
and had Egyptianized his capital of Napata,

01:28:54.700 --> 01:28:57.460
and thus his entire territory.

01:28:57.460 --> 01:29:00.250
He had strong trade connections with Thebes

01:29:00.250 --> 01:29:02.320
and was well versed in the procedure

01:29:02.320 --> 01:29:05.781
of appointing priests and other high officials.

01:29:05.781 --> 01:29:09.730
Piya, 747 to 721 BCE,

01:29:09.730 --> 01:29:14.020
his son strengthened Nubian dominance of Upper Egypt,

01:29:14.020 --> 01:29:16.900
and when the kings of Lower Egypt protested,

01:29:16.900 --> 01:29:19.889
he commanded a large army against them.

01:29:19.889 --> 01:29:21.970
Piya conquered Lower Egypt,

01:29:21.970 --> 01:29:25.270
capturing and subjugating all of the main towns

01:29:25.270 --> 01:29:27.430
before marching back to Napata.

01:29:27.430 --> 01:29:30.310
Egypt was now legally under his rule,

01:29:30.310 --> 01:29:33.370
but he allowed the Lower Egyptian kings to regroup

01:29:33.370 --> 01:29:35.170
and reestablish their power.

01:29:35.170 --> 01:29:36.850
These buffer zones diminished

01:29:36.850 --> 01:29:38.920
during the Third Intermediate Period

01:29:38.920 --> 01:29:41.380
and Egypt lost its prior strength,

01:29:41.380 --> 01:29:43.870
but there were still countries on its boundary,

01:29:43.870 --> 01:29:48.070
such as Judah and Israel that served the same purpose.

01:29:48.070 --> 01:29:51.280
The subjugation of those areas by Shoshenq I

01:29:51.280 --> 01:29:54.460
pushed Egypt's boundary up against the Assyrians

01:29:54.460 --> 01:29:56.170
with no buffer in between.

01:29:56.170 --> 01:29:58.990
Moving forth to the 26th Dynasty,

01:29:58.990 --> 01:30:02.050
Psammetkus I was a powerful ruler,

01:30:02.050 --> 01:30:05.530
who instilled in his people the grandeur of Egypt's past

01:30:05.530 --> 01:30:09.190
by restoring it through massive projects, renovations,

01:30:09.190 --> 01:30:12.130
restorations, and military feats.

01:30:12.130 --> 01:30:16.900
His son, Necho II, 610 to 595 BCE,

01:30:16.900 --> 01:30:18.790
continued his father's legacy

01:30:18.790 --> 01:30:20.980
by conducting military battles,

01:30:20.980 --> 01:30:25.030
ordering construction projects and expanding the military.

01:30:25.030 --> 01:30:27.820
The Egyptians were never great seafarers,

01:30:27.820 --> 01:30:31.570
and Necho II recognized this by establishing a fleet

01:30:31.570 --> 01:30:35.320
of Greek mercenaries, which proved quite successful.

01:30:35.320 --> 01:30:37.810
Necho II is regularly portrayed

01:30:37.810 --> 01:30:40.810
as a great warrior and military commander

01:30:40.810 --> 01:30:43.510
who strengthened the nation he had inherited.

01:30:43.510 --> 01:30:46.090
During the reign of Amasis II,

01:30:46.090 --> 01:30:48.730
he was successful in reforming government spending

01:30:48.730 --> 01:30:51.130
while also stimulating the economy

01:30:51.130 --> 01:30:53.590
and directing war operations.

01:30:53.590 --> 01:30:55.960
Egypt came together behind his leadership

01:30:55.960 --> 01:30:57.730
and thrived once more.

01:30:57.730 --> 01:31:00.520
With a thriving economy, secure boundaries

01:31:00.520 --> 01:31:03.640
and prosperous commerce, building projects,

01:31:03.640 --> 01:31:06.280
temples and other works of art were finished,

01:31:06.280 --> 01:31:10.270
and Egypt's reputation regained some of its lost luster.

01:31:10.270 --> 01:31:13.643
He was replaced by his son, Psammetikus III,

01:31:13.643 --> 01:31:16.450
526 BCE, who was a young

01:31:16.450 --> 01:31:19.660
and inexperienced king who was ill prepared

01:31:19.660 --> 01:31:22.000
for the difficulties he faced.

01:31:22.000 --> 01:31:24.670
Cambyses II, the Persian monarch,

01:31:24.670 --> 01:31:26.470
had sent to Amasis asking

01:31:26.470 --> 01:31:28.570
for one of his daughters as a bride,

01:31:28.570 --> 01:31:30.490
but Amasis not wanting to obey

01:31:30.490 --> 01:31:33.130
but also trying to prevent confrontation

01:31:33.130 --> 01:31:37.420
sent Apries's daughter instead, who was his predecessor.

01:31:37.420 --> 01:31:39.340
This former Egyptian princess

01:31:39.340 --> 01:31:42.880
was profoundly offended by Amasis's choice,

01:31:42.880 --> 01:31:46.210
particularly since it had long been Egyptian policy

01:31:46.210 --> 01:31:50.350
not to transfer noble women to foreign monarchs as wives.

01:31:50.350 --> 01:31:53.290
When she arrived Cambyses II's palace,

01:31:53.290 --> 01:31:55.450
she disclosed her true identity,

01:31:55.450 --> 01:31:58.409
and Cambyses II vowed revenge

01:31:58.409 --> 01:32:02.174
Amasis's slander by sending him a fake bride.

01:32:02.174 --> 01:32:05.007
(dramatic music)

01:32:07.642 --> 01:32:10.142
(tense music)

01:32:15.346 --> 01:32:18.096
(dramatic music)

01:32:27.031 --> 01:32:29.800
Unlike Cambyses, Darius wanted to govern

01:32:29.800 --> 01:32:31.750
Egypt in his absence.

01:32:31.750 --> 01:32:33.100
He ascended to the throne

01:32:33.100 --> 01:32:36.850
of the Achaemenid Empire in 522 BCE,

01:32:36.850 --> 01:32:39.280
and toured Egypt at least twice,

01:32:39.280 --> 01:32:41.500
though he favored Egypt from afar.

01:32:41.500 --> 01:32:43.960
Nonetheless, he adored the culture

01:32:43.960 --> 01:32:46.450
and directed funds towards the reconstruction

01:32:46.450 --> 01:32:50.500
of destroyed temples and the dedication of new ones.

01:32:50.500 --> 01:32:54.040
In keeping with the Persian practice of religious tolerance,

01:32:54.040 --> 01:32:58.420
Darius praise the Egyptian gods with presents and statues.

01:32:58.420 --> 01:33:00.910
He is widely viewed as having a gentler hand

01:33:00.910 --> 01:33:03.010
with Egypt than Cambyses.

01:33:03.010 --> 01:33:05.050
For the second Persian conquest

01:33:05.050 --> 01:33:07.360
of Greece in 480 BCE,

01:33:07.360 --> 01:33:11.390
his son Xerxes I, 486 to 465 BCE,

01:33:12.790 --> 01:33:14.277
relied on all the resources

01:33:14.277 --> 01:33:17.980
of the Achaemenid Empire, including Egypt.

01:33:17.980 --> 01:33:20.200
When the Persians were defeated at Salamis

01:33:20.200 --> 01:33:25.120
in 480 BCE and Plataea in 479 BCE,

01:33:25.120 --> 01:33:27.250
Xerxes abandoned foreign affairs

01:33:27.250 --> 01:33:29.350
in favor of construction projects

01:33:29.350 --> 01:33:32.380
and different relationships with court ladies.

01:33:32.380 --> 01:33:37.380
Artaxerxes I, 465 to 424 BCE, succeeded him

01:33:38.380 --> 01:33:40.360
and battled for six years

01:33:40.360 --> 01:33:43.690
to put down the first significant Egyptian rebellion,

01:33:43.690 --> 01:33:48.690
led by Inaros II, the Libyan royal son of Psamtik V,

01:33:49.180 --> 01:33:53.163
encouraged and assisted by Athens in 460 to 454 BCE.

01:33:54.820 --> 01:33:56.650
While it is true that the Persians

01:33:56.650 --> 01:34:00.820
ruled Egypt during the 27th and 31st Dynasties,

01:34:00.820 --> 01:34:03.370
Egyptian culture was kept alive,

01:34:03.370 --> 01:34:05.830
and the 30th Dynasty of Egyptian rulers

01:34:05.830 --> 01:34:09.370
gave Egypt back a brief time of its former glory,

01:34:09.370 --> 01:34:12.490
before the Persians invaded their land again.

01:34:12.490 --> 01:34:17.490
This era comprises the 27th to 31st Dynasties of Egypt.

01:34:17.920 --> 01:34:20.320
Egyptian resistance to Persian control,

01:34:20.320 --> 01:34:23.440
on the other hand, is visible throughout the area,

01:34:23.440 --> 01:34:25.780
and Egypt thrived under Persian rule

01:34:25.780 --> 01:34:28.780
because the Persian shahs respected the culture.

01:34:28.780 --> 01:34:31.245
Amyrtaeus of the 28th Dynasty,

01:34:31.245 --> 01:34:34.210
Nectanebo II and Nectanebo II

01:34:34.210 --> 01:34:37.240
all governed the nation, commanded troops,

01:34:37.240 --> 01:34:40.060
and participated in construction projects

01:34:40.060 --> 01:34:42.940
in the manner of the great pharaohs of the past.

01:34:42.940 --> 01:34:46.240
Whoever was behind the revolts against Persian authority,

01:34:46.240 --> 01:34:49.270
Egypt's second conquest did not last long.

01:34:49.270 --> 01:34:54.250
Philip II of Macedon, 359 to 336 BCE,

01:34:54.250 --> 01:34:56.230
defeated the Greek city states

01:34:56.230 --> 01:34:59.290
and incorporated them into Macedonian authority.

01:34:59.290 --> 01:35:01.693
When he was murdered in 336 BCE,

01:35:02.719 --> 01:35:07.060
he was preparing a grand expedition to subjugate Persia.

01:35:07.060 --> 01:35:09.010
He already had all of the means

01:35:09.010 --> 01:35:11.110
he would require for the conquest,

01:35:11.110 --> 01:35:14.860
which he entrusted to his son, Alexander.

01:35:14.860 --> 01:35:16.960
The pharaohs of the 30th Dynasty

01:35:16.960 --> 01:35:19.210
upheld Egyptians kingship's honor

01:35:19.210 --> 01:35:21.100
and left their impressive structures

01:35:21.100 --> 01:35:23.950
in the footsteps of those who came before them.

01:35:23.950 --> 01:35:26.650
So while the late period may be considered

01:35:26.650 --> 01:35:29.050
the end of Egyptian sovereignty,

01:35:29.050 --> 01:35:31.030
it should not be considered the end

01:35:31.030 --> 01:35:33.010
of Egyptian civilization.

01:35:33.010 --> 01:35:35.770
Even today, Egypt's cultural accomplishments

01:35:35.770 --> 01:35:38.530
inspire respect, if not fear,

01:35:38.530 --> 01:35:40.990
and remain among the most popular

01:35:40.990 --> 01:35:43.660
and intriguing of the old world.

01:35:43.660 --> 01:35:46.570
Although times changed, current modern Egypt

01:35:46.570 --> 01:35:49.030
in the 21st century might look like

01:35:49.030 --> 01:35:51.730
a coming forward version of ancient Egypt.

01:35:51.730 --> 01:35:55.360
The Nile River is still sacred to the Egyptian people,

01:35:55.360 --> 01:35:57.730
and they still celebrate the same festivals

01:35:57.730 --> 01:36:01.240
of the ancient times, such as the spring festivals.

01:36:01.240 --> 01:36:05.290
The food is quite inspired by the authentic ancient food.

01:36:05.290 --> 01:36:07.030
The traditions are still there,

01:36:07.030 --> 01:36:09.010
and even the last development form

01:36:09.010 --> 01:36:11.920
of the ancient language called the Coptic

01:36:11.920 --> 01:36:15.550
is still spoken in Egypt in church's prayers

01:36:15.550 --> 01:36:18.100
and the middle of their Arabic dialect.

01:36:18.100 --> 01:36:20.890
The modern people are proud of the legacy.

01:36:20.890 --> 01:36:23.890
It was seen in the parades that were done in Cairo

01:36:23.890 --> 01:36:25.870
for the transportation of the mummies

01:36:25.870 --> 01:36:27.910
to the Civilizations Museum,

01:36:27.910 --> 01:36:31.720
and the reopening of the alley of the sphinxes in Luxor.

01:36:31.720 --> 01:36:33.250
They're building new cities,

01:36:33.250 --> 01:36:35.230
digging their way to improve commerce

01:36:35.230 --> 01:36:38.020
with the highways dug in the middle of the mountains

01:36:38.020 --> 01:36:39.790
passing through the deserts.

01:36:39.790 --> 01:36:42.250
They're almost opening the biggest museum

01:36:42.250 --> 01:36:44.080
in the whole world.

01:36:44.080 --> 01:36:46.780
Excavations unearth every day

01:36:46.780 --> 01:36:49.030
new discoveries which might lead soon

01:36:49.030 --> 01:36:51.130
to a discovery similar to that

01:36:51.130 --> 01:36:55.210
of the tomb of Tutankhamun in 1922.

01:36:55.210 --> 01:36:59.800
And this land will always remain an attractive mystery,

01:36:59.800 --> 01:37:01.870
dazzling and enchanting people

01:37:01.870 --> 01:37:06.382
from all over the world with its magic and history.

01:37:06.382 --> 01:37:09.632
(gentle upbeat music)

